{In this game we will see a rare way of playing in this structure in which
White goes for the endgame straight from the opening.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3.
Bf4 c5 4. d5 e6 5. f3 Nf6 6. e4 exd5 7. exd5 d6 8. Bb5+ $5 Nbd7 9. Qe2+ {
Forcing the exchange of queens.} Qe7 10. Nc3 a6 11. Bxd7+ Kxd7 {[%cal Gd7c7]} (
11... Bxd7 {is also fine for Black, but Black decides to transfer his king to
the queenside.}) 12. O-O-O Qxe2 13. Ngxe2 b5 {[%cal Gc8b7]} 14. g4 $1 {[%cal
Ge2g3] a typical pawn move for White. This helps White to gain space on the
kingside.} Bb7 15. Ng3 h6 16. Nge4 Ne8 17. Rhe1 $11 {White has organized his
pieces well. He has more space in the centre as well as on the kingside. But
Black remains solid and has the bishop pair. It is not so easy for White to
breakthrough. The game ultimately ended in a draw.} Rd8 18. g5 Be7 19. gxh6
gxh6 20. Re2 f5 21. Ng3 Ng7 22. Rg2 Rde8 23. Nb1 Bf6 24. c4 bxc4 25. Na3 Bd4
26. Nxc4 Bxd5 27. Nxd6 Ref8 28. Rgd2 Bxf3 29. Rf1 Bg4 30. Nc4 Ne6 31. Bd6 Rd8
32. Bxc5 Nxc5 33. Rxd4+ Ke6 34. Re1+ Kf6 35. Nd6 h5 36. Rf1 Ke5 37. Rxg4 fxg4
38. Nf7+ Kd4 39. Nxd8 Rxd8 40. Nxh5 Rh8 41. Rf5 Nd3+ 42. Kc2 Ke3 43. Nf6 Rxh2+
44. Kc3 Rh4 45. Ra5 Nf4 46. Ra3 Ke2 47. Kc2 Ng2 48. Nxg4 Ne1+ 49. Kc3 Rxg4 50.
Rxa6 Rg3+ 51. Kc4 Rg4+ 52. Kc3 Rg3+ 1/2-1/2

