1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. d5 e6 ({More popular continuation is} 4...
Qb6 {[%csl Rb2] with an attempt to force a concession in white's camp.}) 5. f3
({Giving the control over the centre should not be recommended for white:} 5.
dxe6 fxe6 6. e3 Qf6 7. c3 Bd6 (7... d5 $5 8. Nf3 Nc6) 8. Nd2 Nxd2 9. Bxd6 Nxf1
10. Kxf1 b6 11. Nf3 Bb7 12. h4 Nc6 13. Rh3 $14 {1-0 Adams,M-Adorjan,A/Manila
1992/TD (35)}) 5... Nf6 (5... Bd6 6. Bxd6 Nxd6 7. Qd2 O-O 8. e4 b5 (8... exd5
9. Qxd5 Qb6 10. Qb3 Qa5+ 11. Nc3 Nc6 12. O-O-O Nd4 13. Qd5 Qc7 14. Nge2 $16 {
1-0 Stefanova,A-Van Elst,A/Montpellier 2000/EXT 2001 (88)}) 9. Nc3 Qb6 10. b3
e5 11. Nh3 Na6 12. Rb1 Rb8 13. Be2 b4 14. Na4 Qc7 15. Nb2 f5 $15 {0-1 Cornette,
M-Hamdouchi,H/Nice 2003/CBM 97 ext (57)}) ({Risky, but deserves further
investigation is:} 5... Qf6 6. Bxb8 Qxb2 7. fxe4 Qxa1 8. Bf4 Qxa2 9. Bd2 b5 10.
c4 b4 11. e3 a5 12. Bd3 a4 13. Nf3 Ba6 14. O-O Bxc4 15. Bxc4 Qxc4 16. Ne5 Qxe4
17. Nxf7 Rg8 18. dxe6 Qxe6 19. Qf3 Ra7 20. Ng5 Qc4 21. Rc1 Qb3 22. Bxb4 h6 23.
Nd2 Qa2 24. Qe4+ Kd8 25. Qf4 cxb4 26. Qb8+ Ke7 27. Qe5+ {1/2-1/2 Piket,J-Comp
Gideon 2/The Hague 1994/EXT 99 (27)}) (5... Qa5+ 6. c3 Nf6 {appeared few times
in practice as well.}) 6. e4 {White has two alternative ways to defend the Pd5.
} (6. c4 Nh5 7. Be3 d6 8. Nc3 e5 9. Bf2 Be7 10. e4 O-O 11. Nge2 g6 12. g4 Ng7
13. h4 Na6 14. Qd2 $14 {1-0 Golod,V-Adamson,R/Las Vegas USA 2004/The Week in
Chess 503 (68)}) (6. Nc3 Nh5 (6... d6 7. e4 a6 8. Qd2 exd5 9. Nxd5 Nxd5 10.
Qxd5 Qf6 11. Bc1 Nc6 12. c3 Be6 13. Qg5 Qxg5 14. Bxg5 f6 15. Be3 d5 $11 {
1/2-1/2 Maksimovic,B-Pavlovic,M/Belgrade 1999/EXT 2000 (55)}) 7. Be3 d6 8. Qd2
Be7 9. Bf2 O-O 10. e3 Nf6 11. Bc4 Na6 12. Nge2 Nc7 13. e4 exd5 14. exd5 a6 15.
a4 b6 16. Nf4 Bd7 $132 {[%cal Gb6b5] 1/2-1/2 Piket,J-Shaked,T/Merrillville
1997/CBM 62 (37)}) 6... exd5 7. exd5 d6 {White has obvious space advantage,
but the pawn on f3 obstructs his development.} 8. Nc3 (8. Bb5+ Nbd7 9. a4 a6
10. Be2 Nh5 11. Be3 g6 12. Nh3 Bg7 13. Nc3 O-O 14. g4 Re8 15. Qd2 Nhf6 $15 {
0-1 Granovski,A-Maksimenko,A/Moscow 1991/TD (30)}) (8. c4 Be7 9. Ne2 O-O 10.
Ng3 Re8 11. Be2 Nbd7 12. Nc3 Bf8 13. O-O Ne5 14. Qc2 Bd7 15. Rfe1 a6 16. a4 h6
17. Bd2 $14 {1-0 Bredl,H-Lechtynsky,J/Bayern 2002/EXT 2003 (56)}) 8... Be7 9.
Qd2 a6 $146 {[%cal Gb7b5]} (9... O-O 10. O-O-O a6 11. Nge2 b5 12. Ng3 c4 13.
Be2 Nbd7 14. Nf5 Nc5 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Rhe1 Qc7 17. Bg5 Nfd7 18. Be7 Re8 19.
Bxc4 Bb7 20. Bb3 f6 21. Re6 Nxe6 22. dxe6 Nc5 23. Bxd6 Nxb3+ 24. axb3 Qc8 25.
e7 $16 {1-0 Savchenko,S-Golubev,M/Luzern 1994/EXT 99 (42)}) 10. a4 O-O 11. Nge2
Re8 12. g4 {White wants to grab as more space as possible.} Qa5 $1 {Black is
intending to carry out b7-b5 advance gaining space on the queenside.} 13. Ng3 (
13. Ra3 {prevents b7-b5, but wastes an important tempo. After} Nbd7 14. Ng3 Nb6
$1 {[%csl Rd5] white is losing Pd5.}) 13... b5 14. g5 b4 15. Nce2 $1 {The side
that has space advantage should avoid exchanges, so the move in the text is
correct.} (15. Nce4 $6 Nxe4 16. Nxe4 Bf5 $15) 15... Nfd7 16. Ne4 {[%csl Rd6]}
Qc7 17. a5 {Preventing from black the manouevre Nd7-b6 as well as a6-a5
followed by Bc8-a6.} Bf8 18. N2g3 Ne5 {[%csl Rf3]} 19. Kf2 Nbd7 20. h4 f5 $1 {
Black must act decisively, otherwise his position will be simply cramped.} 21.
gxf6 ({I think that white could go for:} 21. Nxf5 Nxf3 $1 22. Nh6+ $1 (22. Kxf3
Ne5+ 23. Bxe5 Bxf5 {[%csl Re4,Re5]} 24. Ng3 Rxe5 25. Nxf5 Rxf5+ 26. Kg2 Qf7 $17
) 22... gxh6 23. Kxf3 Ne5+ 24. Kg2 {with a sharp position, but white should
not be worse.}) 21... Nxf6 22. Nxf6+ gxf6 23. Bh6 $6 {It's illogical to
exchange black's passive bishop.} (23. h5 $1 $13 {preventing Ne5-g6.}) 23...
Kh8 24. h5 Qf7 25. Bxf8 Qxf8 26. Bh3 $6 {This exchange favours black as well.}
({Possible was} 26. Qf4 $15) 26... Bxh3 27. Rxh3 f5 {Black has now nearly
winning advantage due to numerous factors, namely: strong Ne5 compared to his
counterpart, vulnerable position of white's king and Pd5 weakness.} 28. Qg5 (
28. Rh4 Qf6 29. Rf4 Qg5 30. Rd4 f4 $1 31. Qxf4 Qd8 32. Re4 Rf8 $19) 28... h6 $1
29. Qf4 (29. Qxf5 Qg7 {[%csl Rf2,Rf3][%cal Ge8f8,Gf8f2]} 30. Ne4 Rf8 31. Qe6
Rae8 32. Qxd6 Nc4 $19) 29... Ng4+ $1 {With help of small tactical trick Shirov
transfers his knight to e3, which decides the game quickly.} 30. Kg1 (30. fxg4
fxg4 $19 {[%csl Rf4,Rh3]}) 30... Ne3 {[%csl Rc2,Rd5]} 31. Rh2 Qg7 32. Rd2 Re5
33. Kh2 Nxd5 {Black won a pawn and his attack is irresistible.} 34. Qh4 f4 35.
Ne4 Rg8 36. Kh1 Ne3 37. Nxd6 Rd5 38. Qh2 Rxd2 39. Qxd2 Qd7 {[%cal Rd7h3]} 0-1

