{In the next two games we see an idea for White where he prefers to recapture
on d5 with a piece rather than a pawn.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 c5 3. d5 Ne4 4. Bf4 e6
5. f3 Nf6 6. Nc3 $5 {[%cal Ge2e4] White wants to maintain a hold on the
d5-square by recapturing with a piece. If Black does not take on d5
immediately, then White is ready to strengthen the centre with e2-e4.} Nxd5 7.
Nxd5 exd5 8. Qxd5 Qf6 $6 {[%cal Rf6f4,Rf6b2,Gf6e6] Double attacking Bf4 and
pawn on b2. Black also prefers to offer the exchange of queens with ...Qe6
next and try to regain control of the d5-square before White settles down and
puts a clamp on d5. But this strategy ignores Black's development and is not
the best for Black.} (8... Nc6 $142 9. O-O-O d6 {[%cal Gc8e6] with the idea to
play ...Be6 with a playable position for Black.}) 9. Be5 Qe6 10. e4 Nc6 11. Bc3
$6 {This allows Black to force the exchange of his knight for White's dark
square bishop.} (11. Bg3 $1 {was the correct retreat of the bishop.} Qxd5 12.
exd5 Nb4 {is nothing to worry about because of,} 13. O-O-O $1 {[%csl Gd5]}
Nxa2+ 14. Kb1 Nb4 15. c3 Na6 {and now after the strong} 16. d6 $18 {[%csl Rc8,
Re8,Rf8] White gains a winning advantage as all Black's pieces are immobile!})
11... Qxd5 12. exd5 Nb4 $1 {forcing the exchange of White's dark square bishop.
} 13. Bxb4 cxb4 14. O-O-O Bd6 $11 {Black has a weak pawn structure on the
queenside but his bishop pair compensates for this weakness. The position
remains balanced.} 15. g3 h5 16. Nh3 h4 17. f4 Kf8 18. Bg2 b6 19. Ng5 Bb7 20.
Bh3 Bc5 21. Bxd7 hxg3 22. hxg3 Rxh1 23. Rxh1 Bxd5 24. Rd1 Bc4 25. b3 Be2 26.
Rd5 Rd8 27. Kd2 Bb5 28. Bc6 Rxd5+ 29. Bxd5 Be8 30. Ne4 Bg1 31. Nd6 Bh2 32. Nxe8
Kxe8 33. c3 Bxg3 34. f5 bxc3+ 1/2-1/2

