{This game is a nice example of how to create a strong kingside attack against
Black's fianchetto setup.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. f3 Nf6 5. d5 d6 6.
e4 g6 7. Nc3 Bg7 8. Qd2 O-O 9. Bh6 Bxh6 10. Qxh6 e6 {Black decides to open up
the centre in search of counterplay against white's kingside attack. But as we
will soon see it does not help Black.} 11. O-O-O exd5 12. exd5 Re8 13. Nge2 a6
14. Ng3 $1 b5 15. Nce4 {Exchaning the lone defender on Black's kingside - The
f6-knight.} Nxe4 16. Nxe4 f5 (16... Ra7 {[%cal Ga7h7] was the best try for
Black, indenting to include the rook in the defence via the 7th Rank.} 17. h4
f5 18. Ng5 Qf6 19. h5 $40 {[%cal Rh5g6] with the idea to play hxg6, still
gives White strong attacking chances on the h-file.}) 17. Ng5 Qe7 $2 {[#]} (
17... Ra7 18. h4 {transposes}) 18. Bxb5 $1 $18 {[%cal Rh1e1] a beautiful way
to bring White's rook in the attack.} Qe3+ (18... axb5 19. Rhe1 Qd7 20. Rxe8+
Qxe8 21. Qxh7+ $18) 19. Kb1 Re7 {[#]} 20. Be8 $1 Qe5 21. Rhe1 {and it is game
over. A nice attacking game by GM Adams.} 1-0

