{This game deals with the pawn structure after Black captures White's pawn on
b2.} 1. d4 c5 2. d5 Nf6 3. Bg5 Ne4 4. Bf4 Qb6 {This is the main move for Black.
} 5. Nd2 $1 Nxd2 (5... Qxb2 {is the best move for Black, which we will see in
future games.}) 6. Bxd2 Qxb2 7. Nf3 {[%csl Ge5][%cal Ye2e4] I believe this is
better than playing 7.e4. The point is to first cover the e5-square, thus
preventing ...Qe5 in reply to e4, which creates problems for the e4-pawn.} (7.
e4 Qe5 {is annoying for White.}) 7... Qb6 $6 (7... Qa3 {it is better to place
the queen actively on a3 rather than retreating it all the way back!} 8. e4 g6
$44 {[%cal Gf8g7] with the idea to play ...Bg7 with a fine position for Black,
although, White has good compensation for the pawn.}) 8. Bc3 {preventing ...
g6 and ...Bg7.} d6 9. e4 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 $5 {[%cal Gf3f4] an
interesting recapture. The idea is to cover the e5-square with f3-f4.} (11.
Qxf3 $16 {is objectively better.}) 11... Nd7 12. f4 {[%csl Ge5]} Rg8 13. e5 {
Time to open up the position.} dxe5 14. fxe5 Nxe5 $2 {Black decides to win
more material, but it backfires badly.} 15. Bxe5 Qb4+ 16. Qd2 Qe4+ 17. Qe3 Qxh1
18. O-O-O Kd8 19. Qxc5 Rc8 20. Qa5+ b6 21. Qxa7 {[%csl Rd8] and Blacks king is
about to be checkmated.} Rxc2+ 22. Kxc2 Qe4+ 23. Kb3 Qxe5 1-0

