{This is another game by GM Nikola Sedlak which is very similar to the
previous game.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. d5 Qb6 5. Nd2 Nxd2 6. Bxd2
Qxb2 7. Nf3 Qb6 8. Bc3 d6 9. e4 Bg4 10. h3 Bxf3 11. gxf3 $5 Nd7 12. f4 a6 13.
a4 {this is a typical reaction to ...a6, preventing any future ...b5 advance.}
Rg8 14. e5 g6 {this is a better way to resist in this position. In the
previous game, Black collapsed quickly.} 15. e6 Nf6 16. a5 Qc7 17. exf7+ $6 (
17. Bxf6 $1 exf6 18. Bc4 f5 19. Qd2 Bg7 20. Rb1 $16 {[%csl Gd5,Ge6][%cal Rb1b7]
White stands clearly better due to the active pawns on e6-d5 and the open
b-file.}) 17... Kxf7 18. h4 Bg7 19. Bh3 Nh5 20. Be6+ Kf8 21. Bxg7+ Kxg7 22. f5
Rgf8 23. Qd2 c4 24. Rg1 c3 25. Qd4+ Nf6 26. h5 Qc5 27. Qh4 Rab8 28. Rxg6+ hxg6
29. h6+ Kh7 30. fxg6+ Kxg6 31. Qg3+ Kxh6 32. Qf4+ Kg7 33. Qg3+ Kh8 34. Ra4 Nh7
35. Rh4 Qxf2+ 36. Qxf2 Rxf2 37. Kxf2 Kg7 38. Rg4+ Kh6 39. Rb4 Nf6 40. Ke3 Kg5
41. Kd3 Ne8 42. Rg4+ Kf6 43. Rf4+ Kg6 44. Rf8 b6 45. axb6 Rxb6 46. Rxe8 Rb7 47.
Ra8 Rb6 48. Kxc3 1-0

