{This game denotes the best way to play for Black against 4.d5.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. d5 Qb6 5. Nd2 Qxb2 $1 {this seems to be much better than
5...Nxd2.} 6. Nxe4 Qb4+ {[%cal Rb4e4,Rb4e1]} 7. c3 Qxe4 8. e3 {[%csl Re4][%cal
Gg1f3,Gc3c4,Gf1d3] White's plan is to play Nf3 - c4 - Bd3 and gain grounds in
the centre at the same time harass the Black queen.} g5 $1 {This is the best
move for Black, intending to develop his dark square bishop with a tempo.} 9.
Bg3 (9. Bxg5 Qe5 10. Nf3 Qxc3+ 11. Nd2 $44 {is another rare alternative for
White, where White can look out for compensation for the pawns.}) 9... Bg7 10.
Rc1 d6 11. Nf3 Qg6 12. h4 $1 {Hoping to create some weaknesses on Black's
kingside.} h6 13. Bd3 f5 14. Qc2 {[%csl Rf5] It is time to target the f5-pawn.}
O-O $1 {[%csl Gf5] Black adds further support to the f5-pawn. Even though the
kingside is about to be open after hxg5, there is no need to worry for Black
as his king is safely guarded by the g7-bishop and the queen on g6.
Objectively Black stands clearly better but practically it is not easy for
Black to face the compensation.} 15. hxg5 hxg5 16. Bh2 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Gg2g4]}
Qf6 (16... Na6 $1 {is the best move for Black which is tough to play
especially when things are heating up on the kingside.} 17. g4 Bd7 $17 {
[%cal Gc5c4,Ga8c8] with the idea to play ...c4 and open up lines on the
queenside. Black has a clear advantage.}) 17. g4 fxg4 18. Bh7+ Kf7 19. Nd2 Ke8
20. Ne4 Qf3 21. Rg1 Bf5 $2 {The first step in the wrong direction.} ({It was
essential to play ...Kd8 preventing any Bxd6 tricks.} 21... Kd8 $19) 22. Bxf5
Qxf5 23. Bxd6 $132 {with this tactical trick White manages to regain her hopes
and in the end she managed to draw this topsy-turvy game.} Nd7 24. Bg3 Qxd5 25.
Rd1 Qf5 26. Qd3 Rc8 27. Qd5 Qxd5 28. Rxd5 Nf6 29. Rxc5 Rxc5 30. Nxc5 Kf7 31.
Be5 b6 32. Nd3 Rc8 33. Bd4 Ke6 1/2-1/2

