{This is an instructive game by GM Nihal. 5.dxc5 is the most popular move
against Black's immediate knight retreat with 4...Nf6.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3.
Bf4 c5 4. f3 Nf6 5. dxc5 $1 {I think it is best for White to go into this
structure if Black plays an immediate ...Nf6. We enter some sort of Sicilian
pawn structure after dxc5.} Na6 (5... Qa5+ {[%cal Ga5e1,Ga5c5] is the main way
of recapturing the c5 pawn.} 6. Nc3 Qxc5 7. e4 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1] with a
pleasant position for White. The main plan is to play Qd2 followed by 0-0-0.})
6. Nc3 Nxc5 7. e4 d6 8. Qd2 {[%cal Ge1c1]} Ne6 9. Be3 g6 10. O-O-O Bg7 {
We have a structure similar to the Sicilian Dragon. It is clear that White is
ahead in development since Black wasted a few moves with his knight jumps from
b8 to e6.} 11. h4 {White starts to create pressure straight away on the
kingside.} h5 12. Nh3 Bd7 13. Bc4 Rc8 14. Bb3 {[%csl Gb3][%cal Gb3g8] Nihal
places his bishop on a nice a2-g8 diagonal from where it will be useful in
creating an attack.} O-O 15. Bh6 {a typical idea for White, exchanging the
dark square bishops weakens Black's defences.} b5 16. Bxg7 Kxg7 17. Kb1 a5 {[#]
} 18. Bxe6 $1 {a surprising exchange, but it has a strong positional basis!}
fxe6 (18... Bxe6 19. Nxb5 $16 {White simply wins a pawn.}) 19. e5 $1 {This is
the point behind exchanging on e6. White destroys Black's pawn structure
completely.} dxe5 20. Ng5 Qc7 {[#]} 21. Qxd7 $1 {a nice tactical blow this
time!} Qxd7 22. Rxd7 Nxd7 23. Nxe6+ Kf6 24. Nxf8 Nxf8 25. Nxb5 $18 {White is a
clear pawn up and has a winning advantage in this endgame.} Ne6 26. Nc3 Nd4 27.
Ne4+ Kf5 28. c3 Ne2 29. Re1 Nf4 30. g3 Nd5 31. Re2 a4 32. a3 Nb6 33. Kc2 Nc4
34. Nf2 Rb8 35. Nd3 Rb5 36. Re4 Nb6 37. c4 Ra5 38. Kc3 Nd7 39. Kb4 Ra8 40. c5
Nf6 41. Rxe5# 1-0

