{This is game shows an interesting but rare idea where White sacrifices a
couple of pawns in order to snatch the initiative in the opening.} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. f3 Qa5+ 5. c3 Nf6 6. d5 Qb6 7. e4 $5 {White does not care
about his pawns.} (7. Bc1 {is the main move for White.}) 7... Qxb2 8. Nd2 Qxc3
{[#]} 9. Bc7 $1 {[%csl Ga5,Rc3] This is a very important move for White's
sacrificial ideas to succeed. With 9.Bc7 White covers the a5-square which
Black was intending to make use for the safe retreat of his queen. In the next
few moves, White will aim to gain tempos on the exposed Black queen by
developing his pieces at the same time.} d6 10. Bb5+ Bd7 11. a4 $1 {[%csl Gb5]
Ensuring that the queenside is locked properly.} g6 12. Ne2 {[%csl Rc3] The
first attack!} Qe3 13. Nc4 {[%csl Re3][%cal Ge1g1] The second one! White
improves the position of his knight and also prepares to 0-0 next.} Qg5 14. O-O
Bg7 {[#]} 15. Ba5 $1 {[%cal Ra5d2] a nice manoeuvre! The bishop comes back to
haunt the Black queen again!} Nh5 16. Bd2 Qh4 17. Rb1 O-O 18. Qc1 {[%csl Rh4]
[%cal Rd2g5]} h6 19. Be1 Qg5 20. f4 Qg4 {[#]} 21. Ne3 $1 {Time to cash in on
the initiative by winning material!} Bxb5 22. Nxg4 Bxe2 23. Bc3 Bxf1 24. Bxg7
Nxg7 25. Kxf1 $18 {White has a winning advantage} h5 26. Nh6+ Kh7 27. f5 b6 28.
Qg5 Nd7 29. Qxe7 Ne5 30. f6 Kxh6 31. Qxd6 Rfe8 32. fxg7 Kxg7 33. Qc7 Nc4 34.
Re1 Nd2+ 35. Kg1 Nxe4 36. h3 h4 37. Rf1 Nf6 38. Qf4 Nh5 39. Qxf7+ Kh6 40. d6
Rad8 41. d7 Re2 42. Rd1 Re4 43. Rd6 Nf4 44. Qf6 1-0

