{This game shows a cool way for White to reach a pleasant though equal endgame.
} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 c5 3. d5 Ne4 4. Bf4 Qb6 5. Bc1 e6 6. f3 Nf6 7. c4 exd5 8.
cxd5 c4 9. Nc3 {I believe this to be a better move order for White than
playing 9.e3, which is also a fine alternative. By playing Na3 first we
prevent any ...Qa5+ followed by ...b5 ideas.} Bc5 10. e3 $1 {[%csl Rc5,Ge3]
it's important to put the pawn on e3 in order to limit Black's dark square
bishop.} O-O 11. Bxc4 Bxe3 12. Bxe3 Qxe3+ 13. Nge2 d6 14. Qd4 $1 {[%csl Gd4]
offering the exchange of queens. If Balck refuses to exchange then White's
queen will be powerful and unchallenged in the centre.} Qxd4 15. Nxd4 Nbd7 16.
Kd2 $11 {This endgame is about equal, but White is a little more comfortable
due to the extra space.} Nb6 17. b3 Bd7 18. Nc2 a6 19. Ne3 Rae8 20. a4 Re5 21.
g4 Rfe8 22. Rhe1 h5 23. h3 a5 24. Kd3 g6 25. Re2 Kg7 26. Kd4 hxg4 27. hxg4 Rh8
28. Bd3 Rh4 29. Rg1 Bc8 30. Be4 Re8 31. Nb5 Rd8 32. Rgg2 Rh1 33. Rb2 Rc1 34.
Rb1 Rxb1 35. Bxb1 Bd7 36. Nc3 Rh8 37. Rb2 Ra8 38. g5 Ne8 39. f4 Nc7 40. f5 Rh8
41. f6+ Kg8 42. Nc4 Nbxd5 43. Nxd5 Ne6+ 44. Kc3 Rh3+ 45. Kd2 Rh2+ 46. Kd1 Rh1+
47. Ke2 Nxg5 48. Bc2 Rh2+ 49. Ke3 Rh3+ 50. Kd2 Rh2+ 51. Kc3 Rh3+ 52. Bd3 Ne4+
53. Kd4 Nc5 54. Ne7+ Kf8 55. Bc2 Be6 56. Nxd6 Nd7 57. Ne4 Rh2 58. Kc3 Rh3+ 59.
Bd3 Rf3 60. Ng5 Rxf6 61. Nc8 Kg8 62. b4 Bg4 63. Ne7+ Kf8 64. Nxg6+ Kg7 65. Ne7
Nb6 66. Rg2 Rf4 67. bxa5 Nxa4+ 68. Kd2 Kf6 69. Nd5+ Kxg5 70. Nxf4 Kxf4 71. Rf2+
Ke5 72. Rxf7 Nc5 73. Kc3 Be6 74. Rg7 Kd6 75. Bb5 Bf5 76. Bc4 Nd7 77. Kd4 Bh3
78. Bd5 Kc7 79. Rg3 Bf1 80. Rc3+ Kb8 1-0

