{This was a nice attacking game by GM Sulskis. This game is also a good
illustration of how to attack when White's king is stuck in the centre.} 1. d4
Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. f3 Qa5+ 5. c3 Nf6 6. d5 Qb6 7. Bc1 e6 8. c4 exd5 9.
cxd5 c4 $1 {[%cal Gf8c5] with the idea to play ...Bc5 and exploit the weakened
g1-a7 diagonal.} 10. e3 Bc5 11. Kf2 $6 {This is not such a bad move but White
should be prepared to face long-term initiative against his king.} (11. Nc3 {
transposes to the previous game.}) 11... O-O 12. Bxc4 Re8 {[%cal Rc5e3]} 13.
Qb3 Qd8 14. Ne2 d6 15. Rd1 a6 16. a4 Nbd7 17. Nd4 Nb6 18. Nc3 $2 (18. a5 $1 {
was a much better move.} Nxc4 19. Qxc4 Nd7 $14 {[%cal Gd7e5] gives Black some
compensation but White seems to be solid.}) 18... Nxc4 19. Qxc4 {[#]} b5 $1 {
The key move that White probably missed. This pawn break based on the tactical
idea that White's rook is hanging on a1 allows Black to snatch the initiative.}
20. Qd3 b4 21. Nc6 Qc7 22. Ne2 {[#]} Nxd5 $1 {Eliminating the cover of the
c6-knight.} 23. Qxd5 Be6 24. Qd3 Qxc6 $17 {[%csl Rf2] Black has regained his
pawn and has a clearly better position due to his bishop pair and White's
uncomfortable king.} 25. b3 a5 26. Nf4 Bc8 $1 {[%cal Gc8a6,Ge6c8] a nice
bishop transfer to a6.} 27. Re1 Ba6 28. Qd2 d5 29. Bb2 d4 30. Bxd4 Rad8 31. Qc2
Rxd4 32. exd4 Bxd4+ 33. Kg3 Bc3 $17 {[%csl Ga6,Gc3,Rg3] Blacks bishops are
dominating and White's king is very weak.} 34. Rxe8+ Qxe8 35. Rd1 g5 {[%cal
Rg5f4]} 36. Nh5 Be1+ $1 37. Kh3 Qe6+ 0-1

