1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. f3 Qa5+ 5. c3 Nf6 6. d5 Qb6 7. Bc1 e6 8. e4 {
[%csl Gd5] This is White's main move in this variation. It makes sense to
support the d5-pawn with our e-pawn which also helps us develop our light
square bishop quickly.} exd5 9. exd5 Be7 10. c4 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Gb1c3] White
solidifies the support to the d5-pawn and prepares to develop his knight to c3.
} (10. Na3 {[%cal Ga3c4] Is another way for White to play which can be seen in
the next game.}) 10... d6 11. Bd3 {[%cal Yc8f5] Preventing ...Bf5 first.} Nbd7
{[%cal Gd7e5]} 12. f4 $1 {[%csl Ge5]} O-O 13. Nc3 Re8 14. Nge2 Nf8 15. Qc2 Bg4
16. O-O Bxe2 17. Bxe2 N6d7 18. Ne4 $16 {White is clearly better because of
more space in the centre and on the kingside as well as the bishop pair which
will be helpful in kingside attack in the future.} f5 $6 {this leads to
further weaknesses in Black's camp.} 19. Nf2 Bf6 20. Bd3 {[%cal Rd3f5]} Re7 {
Black decides to sacrifice the f5-pawn and create counterplay.} (20... g6 21.
g4 fxg4 22. Nxg4 Bg7 23. f5 $18 {White continues to tear apart Black's
kingside with crushing attacking chances.}) 21. Bxf5 Rae8 22. Bd3 $18 {White
is a clear pawn up without much compensation for Black.} Bd4 23. g3 Nf6 24. Kg2
Qc7 25. Rb1 b5 26. b3 Qb7 27. h3 h5 28. Kh2 Qc8 29. Qd1 b4 30. Bb2 Re3 31. Bc1
h4 32. g4 Rg3 33. Nh1 Rxd3 34. Qxd3 Nxg4+ 35. hxg4 Qxg4 36. Rb2 Bxb2 37. Bxb2
Re2+ 38. Rf2 Qxf4+ 39. Kg2 Qg5+ 40. Ng3 Re3 41. Rxf8+ Kxf8 42. Qf5+ Qxf5 43.
Bxg7+ Kf7 44. Nxf5 h3+ 45. Kh2 Rf3 46. Nxd6+ Kxg7 47. Ne4 Kg6 48. Nxc5 Kg5 49.
d6 Kh4 50. Ne4 Re3 51. d7 Rd3 52. Nf6 Rd2+ 53. Kh1 Rd1+ 54. Kh2 Rd2+ 55. Kh1 h2
0-1

