1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. f3 Qa5+ 5. c3 Nf6 6. d5 Qb6 7. Bc1 e6 8. e4
exd5 9. exd5 Bd6 10. Na3 $5 {[%cal Ga3c4,Gc4e3] This is another popular way
for White to continue in this structure. White can use the empty c4-square in
order to transfer his knight to the e3-square.} O-O 11. Bd3 {[%cal Gg1e2]
intending to play Ne2 next.} Re8+ 12. Ne2 Bf8 13. Nc4 {[%cal Rc4b6]} Qd8 {
[%cal Gb7b5] Black gets ready to push ...b5.} 14. Ne3 {[%csl Ge3][%cal Ge3f5]
The White knight is well placed on e3 from where it could further go to f5.} d6
15. O-O Nbd7 16. a4 Ne5 17. Bc2 g6 18. h3 {[%csl Yg4][%cal Gf3f4] covering the
g4-square before playing f3-f4.} Bg7 19. f4 Ned7 20. Ng3 b6 {[%cal Gc8a6]} 21.
Bd3 {[%cal Gd3a6]} a6 22. Bd2 Bb7 23. Qf3 {all White's pieces are activated.}
Qc7 24. c4 b5 25. b3 {[%csl Ga4,Gc4][%cal Yb3a4,Yb3c4]} b4 26. h4 $1 {Time for
action on the kingside.} Kh8 27. h5 Bc8 28. Rae1 {All White's pieces are
perfectly placed while Black's pieces are dumped inside a little space that he
has.} Ra7 29. Nef5 $3 {A beautiful knight sacrifice to open up the kingside.}
gxf5 30. h6 Bxh6 31. Nxf5 Bf8 32. Bc1 {[%cal Rc1b2]} Rxe1 33. Rxe1 Ng8 34. Bb2+
Ndf6 35. Re8 $1 $18 Bxf5 36. Bxf5 Qe7 37. Rxe7 Rxe7 38. g4 Bg7 39. g5 Nd7 40.
Bxg7+ Kxg7 41. Bxd7 Rxd7 42. Qh3 Rc7 43. Kf2 a5 44. Kf3 1-0

