1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. f3 Qa5+ 5. c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 {[%cal Rd2b3,Rb3a5,
Rb3c5] This is more popular then 6.d5. White threatens to play Nb3.} cxd4 7.
Nb3 Qd8 $5 {Black retreats his queen all the way back leaving it upto White to
decide how he wants to recapture on d4.} 8. cxd4 {[%csl Gd4] This is a logical
recapture. White would like to have a pawn in the centre. In this pawn
structure White's knight belongs to c3 and not b3. So we can say that the
knight on b3 is sightly misplaced.} d5 9. e3 {[%cal Gf1d3,Gg1e2] White's
general idea is to play Bd3 followed by Ne2.} e6 10. Rc1 Nc6 11. Bd3 Bb4+ 12.
Kf2 O-O 13. a3 Bd6 14. Bxd6 Qxd6 15. f4 $1 {[%csl Ge5] controlling the
e5-square.} b6 16. Nf3 Bb7 17. Nbd2 {Relocating the misplaced knight on b3.}
Rfc8 18. Ne5 Qd8 19. Qf3 {[%cal Gg2g4,Gg4g5] White will soon start explanding
on the kingside.} Ne4+ 20. Ke2 f5 21. g4 Nxe5 22. fxe5 Rxc1 23. Rxc1 Qh4 24.
Qg2 Rf8 25. Rc7 Rf7 26. Rxf7 Kxf7 27. gxf5 Qh5+ 28. Ke1 exf5 29. Bxe4 fxe4 {
Strategically White's knight is superior to the bishop on b7 as it is limited
because of it's own pawns.} 30. Qf2+ Ke7 31. Nf1 Ba6 $2 {This allows White to
enter with his queen through the queenside.} 32. Ng3 Qf7 33. Qc2 $1 {[%cal
Rc2c7,Rc2a4]} Kf8 34. Qc6 {[%cal Re5e6]} g6 35. e6 Qf3 36. Qa8+ Ke7 37. Qxa7+
Kxe6 38. Qxb6+ Ke7 39. Qa7+ Ke8 40. Qxa6 Qxe3+ 41. Ne2 Qh3 42. Qc6+ Ke7 43. Qb5
Qxh2 44. Qxd5 1-0

