{An interesting game by Salem illustrating the correct way to play in this
structure from the Black Pieces.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. f3 Qa5+ 5.
c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 cxd4 7. Nb3 Qd8 8. cxd4 d5 9. e3 e6 10. Rc1 Bb4+ 11. Kf2 O-O 12.
a3 Be7 13. Bd3 Nc6 14. g4 $6 {This weakens White's kingside. [#]} (14. Ne2 $142
) 14... Nd7 $1 {[%cal Ge6e5] an important knight retreat preparing to break in
the centre with ...e5. This pawn break is essential for Black in order to
exploit White's weak king position.} 15. Qc2 e5 16. Bg3 {[#]} e4 $1 {A strong
move opening up lines against the White king.} 17. Bb5 Qb6 18. Bxc6 bxc6 19.
Nc5 Nxc5 20. dxc5 Qd8 {With exchanges on c5, White has lost his counterplay on
the c-file. Black can now fully focus on attacking the White king.} 21. fxe4
Bxg4 22. Ne2 Bg5 23. h4 Bh6 {[%csl Gh6][%cal Rh6e3]} 24. Bf4 Bxf4 25. Nxf4 dxe4
26. Rcg1 Qd7 $19 {and Black has a winning advantage because of White's exposed
king.} 27. Qxe4 Qd2+ 28. Kg3 Qxb2 29. h5 Rad8 30. h6 Rfe8 31. Qxc6 Bf5 32. Rg2
Rxe3+ 33. Kh4 Qe5 34. Rxg7+ Kh8 35. Rf1 Rh3+ 36. Nxh3 Rd4+ 37. Nf4 Rxf4+ 38.
Rxf4 Qxf4+ 39. Kh5 Bg6+ 0-1

