1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. f3 Qa5+ 5. c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 cxd4 7. Nb3 Qb6 {
The Black queen is better placed on b6 than on d8 that we saw in the previous
two games. But, Black's Quene on b6 also gives White an additional option of
recapturing on d4 with his queen.} 8. Qxd4 Nc6 $5 {Forcing White to exchange
the queens on b6. This weakens Black's pawn structure but also opens the
a-file for his rook.} 9. Qxb6 axb6 {[%cal Ge7e5,Gd7d5] Black is now ready to
push his pawns with ...e5 and ...d5.} 10. Nd4 $1 {[%cal Gd4b5] Playing against
...e5. White also has ideas like Nb5.} Ra5 $5 {an interesting idea by GM
Svidler. He covers the b5-square and prepares to push ...e5 once again as it
is now supported by his rook.} 11. b4 {pushing the rook away from a5.} Ra4 12.
e4 Nxd4 13. cxd4 e6 14. Bb5 Rxb4 15. a4 {White has sacrificed a pawn for more
space and active pieces.} Rxd4 16. Ne2 Rb4 17. Kd2 $6 (17. Nc1 $1 $44 {[%cal
Rc1d3] with the idea of Nd3, harassing the Black rook, was a better try.})
17... Bc5 18. Kc2 Ke7 {[%cal Rd7d5]} 19. Bd2 d5 $1 20. Bxb4 Bxb4 21. Kb3 Bc5
22. e5 Nd7 23. f4 Rg8 24. g3 g5 25. Rhe1 Be3 $17 {Black was clearly better
though in the end, the game ended in a draw.} 26. Kc2 Nc5 27. Ra3 d4 28. Rd1
gxf4 29. Nxd4 f6 30. gxf4 Bxf4 31. exf6+ Kxf6 32. Ne2 e5 33. Nxf4 exf4 34. Rf3
Bf5+ 35. Kc3 Ke5 36. Bc4 Rc8 37. Kb4 Na6+ 38. Kc3 Nc5 39. Kb4 Na6+ 40. Kc3
1/2-1/2

