1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 c5 4. f3 Qa5+ {This check forces white to play
c2-c3, which will rob from white's queenside knight his natural developing
square.} 5. c3 Nf6 6. Nd2 ({Another theoretical line is} 6. d5 {1/2-1/2
Moiseenko,A-Volokitin,A/Kharkov 2004/CBM 103 [Postny,E] (34)}) 6... cxd4 7. Nb3
Qb6 (7... Qf5 8. Bxb8 Rxb8 9. Qxd4 b6 10. e4 Qf4 11. Nh3 Qc7 12. e5 Ng8 13.
O-O-O $36 {1/2-1/2 Nguyen,N-Ilincic,Z/Budapest 2004/CBM 102 ext (54)}) (7...
Qd8 8. Bxb8 (8. cxd4 d5 9. e3 e6 10. Bd3 Nc6 11. Ne2 Nh5 12. O-O Nxf4 13. Nxf4
Bd6 $11 {0-1 Nguyen Ngoc Truong,S-Belezky,S/Budapest 2004/CBM 98 ext (33)})
8... Rxb8 9. Qxd4 a6 10. Qa7 Qc7 11. e4 e6 12. Bxa6 Bd6 13. Bb5 Bxh2 14. Ne2 b6
15. Qxc7 Bxc7 $15 {0-1 Miladinovic,I-Georgiev,K/Skopje 2002/CBM 88 (34)}) 8.
Qxd4 (8. cxd4 {0-1 Hodgson,J-Gelfand,B/Groningen 1996/CBM 57 [Gelfand] (89)})
8... Nc6 (8... Qxd4 9. cxd4 d5 10. e3 e6 11. g4 Nc6 12. Bb5 Bd7 13. a3 $14 {
1-0 Salov,V-Akopian,V/Wijk aan Zee 1993/CBM 34 (43)}) 9. Qxb6 axb6 10. Nd4 (10.
e4 d5 $11) (10. Be3 b5 11. Nd4 Nxd4 12. Bxd4 e6 13. e4 b4 14. Bb5 bxc3 15. Bxc3
Be7 16. Ne2 O-O 17. Nf4 d6 18. a3 Rd8 19. O-O-O $14 {1-0 Miladinovic,I-Grigore,
G/Istanbul 2002/CBM 91 ext (44)}) 10... e5 ({Appeared few times in practice:} 
10... Ra5 $5) 11. Nxc6 exf4 12. Nd4 {Black has an ugly pawn structure, but
usually gets sufficient counterplay using the dark holes in white's camp.} d5 (
12... Bd6 {appeared in the game Aleksandrov, A-Kotronias,V/Istanbul 2003/CBM
96 [Finkel] (1-0,39)}) 13. e3 fxe3 14. Ke2 g6 $6 $146 {This way of development
is too slow.} (14... Bd6 15. Kxe3 O-O 16. Kf2 Bd7 17. Bd3 Bc6 18. Nge2 Nd7 19.
a3 Ne5 20. Rad1 Rfe8 21. g3 g6 22. Nf4 Bc5 $132 {1/2-1/2 Rogers,I-Ftacnik,L/
Znojmo 1999/CBM 70 ext (58)}) (14... Bc5 15. Kxe3 Bd7 16. Bd3 Kd8 17. Nge2 Ne8
18. Kd2 Nc7 19. Bc2 Ne6 20. Bb3 Bc6 21. Rhe1 Re8 22. Rad1 Kc7 23. Kc1 $14 {
1/2-1/2 Depasquale,C-Chapman,M/Canberra 2000/EXT 2001 (37)}) 15. Kxe3 Bh6+ (
15... Bc5 {is probably better, but then it's clear that 14...g6 was faulty.})
16. Kf2 O-O 17. Bb5 Bd7 18. Nge2 Rfe8 19. Rhd1 {[%mdl 16] White has completed
the development and his advantage is undoubtful. Black has no real
compensation for his permanent pawn weaknesses.} Be3+ 20. Kf1 Re5 21. Bxd7 Nxd7
22. Nc2 Nf6 (22... Bc5 23. f4 Rh5 24. b4 Be7 25. h3 $16 {[%csl Rh5]}) 23. Nxe3
Rxe3 24. Nf4 Re5 25. Rd4 Kf8 26. Nd3 Re6 27. Nb4 Ra5 28. Rad1 Re5 {All pieces
are concentrated on the Pd5. Black is not losing immediately, but he can not
hold all his queenside weaknesses in the long run.} 29. a3 h5 30. Nd3 Re6 31.
Nf4 Re5 32. Rb4 Rf5 33. Nd3 Nd7 34. Re1 Rf6 35. Nf4 Rf5 36. Nd3 Rf6 37. Rd4 Rf5
38. Nb4 {It's not so easy to achieve progress for white, so McShane is
torturing his opponent...} Rc5 39. Re2 Nf6 40. Nc2 Ne8 41. Rd3 Nc7 $2 {It's
not so surprising that black finally blundered the exchange. To play such
positions, without any counterplay is extremely difficult.} (41... Rf6 42. Ne3
Rd6 43. Red2 Nf6 44. c4 $18) 42. b4 $1 Rc6 43. Nd4 Rff6 44. Nxc6 bxc6 45. a4
Rd6 46. Ra2 Rd8 47. a5 Rb8 48. Kf2 Nb5 49. Kg3 Nd6 50. Kf4 Ke7 51. h4 Nc4 {
Black puts up a strong resistance, but it's clear that white's win is just a
matter of time here.} 52. g4 f6 53. Rd1 Kf7 54. Re1 Rb7 55. axb6 {White does
not need to keep the passed pawn, the "a" file will be a nice road for the
white rooks.} Nxb6 56. Rea1 Nc8 57. Ra8 Rc7 58. R1a6 Ke7 59. g5 fxg5+ 60. Kxg5
Kf7 61. Kf4 Ke7 62. Ke5 Kf7 63. Kd4 Ke7 64. Kc5 Kd7 65. f4 {Black is in
zugzwang and forced to allow the following exchange of rooks.} Nd6 66. R8a7
Ne4+ 67. Kb6 Rxa7 68. Rxa7+ (68. Rxa7+ Kd6 69. Rc7 $18) 1-0

