1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 Ne4 3. Bf4 d5 4. e3 e6 5. Bd3 Bd6 6. Bxe4 $1 {This exchange
always creates an imbalance.} Bxf4 7. exf4 dxe4 8. Nc3 {[%cal Rc3e4]} Nc6 9.
Nge2 f5 10. Qd2 {White prepares to 0-0-0.} b6 11. O-O-O Ba6 {[#]} 12. d5 $1 {
[%csl Re8] It is generally advised to open up the centre if your king is stuck
in the centre.} exd5 13. Nxd5 Bc4 14. Qc3 $6 (14. Nec3 {[%cal Gd2e3,Gf2f3] was
simpler and stronger to continue for White. The next plan is to play Qe3
followed by f3. For example,} O-O 15. Qe3 Qc8 16. f3 exf3 17. Qxf3 $18 {
[%csl Gd5] White enjoys a huge advantage due to the dominating knight on d5.})
14... Bxd5 15. Qxg7 Rg8 16. Qxh7 Qd6 17. Qxf5 {White has won a lot of pawns
but things are not so clear yet.} Ne7 18. Qh5+ Bf7 19. Qh4 Qe6 $17 {Black is
in control and this position is clearly better for Black, but after a lot of
ups and downs White finally managed to win it.} 20. Nc3 Nf5 21. Qh3 Nd6 22.
Qxe6+ Bxe6 23. g3 O-O-O 24. Nd5 Rh8 25. Ne7+ Kb7 26. h4 Bg4 27. Rd2 Rh6 28. Re1
c6 29. Rxe4 Re8 30. Re1 Kc7 31. Rd3 Be6 32. Rxd6 Rxe7 33. Rd3 Rg7 34. b3 Bf5
35. Rde3 Rd7 36. Re5 Rf6 37. f3 Bh7 38. Re7 Kd6 39. Rxd7+ Kxd7 40. Re5 c5 41.
Rh5 Bg8 42. Kd2 Rd6+ 43. Ke3 Re6+ 44. Kf2 Rd6 45. Rg5 Bf7 46. Re5 Rd2+ 47. Re2
Rd4 48. Ke3 Ke6 49. g4 Kf6 50. h5 Bd5 51. Rh2 Rd1 52. h6 Re1+ 53. Kf2 Re8 54.
f5 Rh8 55. Kg3 Ke5 56. Re2+ Kf6 57. Kf4 Rg8 58. Rd2 Bf7 59. g5+ 1-0

