{This game was played towards the end of the very lengthy tournament. Safarli
was one of the key competitors in the battle for the ever-desired victory.} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 {Tromp! A surprise for my opponent, but also for myself.} Ne4 3.
Bf4 d5 4. e3 c5 5. Bd3 Nf6 {This system, losing two tempi, feels somewhat
unnatural to me, but Black remains of course very solid. His idea is to
develop the c8-bishop before closing the door shut with e6.} 6. c3 Nc6 7. Nd2
Bg4 8. Ngf3 e6 9. Qa4 $5 {Trying to use the advantage in development, like in
the Cambridge Springs Variation, but with few extra moves under my belt!} c4 $5
(9... Nd7 {is the main move and much less committal as well. Eltaj probably
decided that the poor knight had already moved around enough for the first ten
moves.}) 10. Bb1 $5 {A new move according to my database. I liked this
diagonal for the bishop, but on c2 it would make my queen look trapped. Being
a gentleman, this is not what I do to my queens.} (10. Be2 a6 11. Ne5 Bxe2 12.
Kxe2 {Shimanov-Jurcik, 2012}) 10... Bd6 11. Bg5 $5 {Keeping all the pieces on
the board!} ({The natural} 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. b3 {would simplify matters.} (12.
Ne5 $5)) 11... O-O 12. O-O Be7 13. Re1 Rb8 14. b4 $5 {Limiting Black's
counterplay on the queenside.} b5 15. Qd1 a5 16. a3 {The pawn chains might
make one sleepy, but the boringness of the position is delusional. Sooner or
later the centre will get blasted open.} Ra8 (16... e5 {was what I was hoping
for, but things are even messier than I thought.} 17. Qc2 {was my idea...} e4
18. Bxf6 gxf6 $3 (18... Bxf6 19. Nxe4 $1 {is what I was daydreaming about.})
19. Nxe4 {and now time for something pretty-} dxe4 20. Qxe4 f5 $1 21. Qxc6 Rb6
{and the queen is trapped. Who is the gentleman now?}) 17. Bc2 e5 {Now there
is no temptation to go Qc2. I was not happy with this, but life and the game,
continued.} 18. h3 Bxf3 19. Nxf3 Ne4 $6 {Accompanied by the offer of a draw. I
was more worried about 19...e4, so it wasn't hard to refuse this one.} (19...
e4 $1 20. Ne5 Qc7 {and I'm not sure the knight on e5 has as bright a future as
a present.}) 20. Bxe7 Qxe7 (20... Nxe7 {worried me at first, but I don't have
to accept the pawn sacrifice with 21.Bxe4? instead after} 21. dxe5 $1 (21. Bxe4
dxe4 22. Nxe5 f6 23. Ng4 Nd5 {is too pretty to allow}) 21... Nxc3 22. Qd4 $1 {
White is better.}) 21. Bxe4 dxe4 22. Nd2 {The protected d-pawn gave me some
hopes now.} axb4 (22... f5 {allows} 23. a4 $1) 23. axb4 f5 24. d5 $1 {Now
Black is forced to concede the a-file.} (24. Rxa8 {was tempting too, but the
position after} Rxa8 25. f3 exd4 26. exd4 e3 27. f4 {didn't seem that
advantageous for White.}) 24... Rxa1 25. Qxa1 Nd8 26. f3 $1 {Activating the
sleeping knight.} exf3 27. Nxf3 Nf7 28. Qa6 Qd7 $6 (28... Nd6 {is more natural
and better too.} 29. Ra1 {White has some initiative on the queenside. Still
Black should be able to get some counterplay in the centre and on the kingside.
} (29. Ng5 Qxg5 30. Qxd6 Qg3 {with enough counterplay to hold}) 29... h6 $5 {
getting the king out of the way first and stopping any Ng5.} 30. Qb6 Kh7 31.
Ra7 Qf6) 29. Qe6 Rd8 {Here I took some time and came up with a surprisingly
venomous idea.} 30. e4 $1 {Just when everything seemed lost!} fxe4 31. Rxe4
Qxd5 $2 (31... Kf8 $1 {holds after a surreal sequence of cold-blooded only
moves.} 32. Nxe5 Qxd5 33. Qf5 g6 34. Qf6 (34. Qf4 $2 {is met with} Re8 $1)
34... Rd6 35. Qf4 g5 $1 36. Qf5 Kg7 {and White has nothing better than
simplifying when Black gets a draw} 37. Rd4 Qe6 38. Qxe6 Rxe6 39. Nxf7 Kxf7 40.
Rd5 Kf6 41. Rxb5 Re3) 32. Rxe5 $1 {Now White gets a nice pull. This is not the
sort of simplification that my opponent was looking for.} Qxe6 33. Rxe6 Kf8 34.
Nd4 {The b5-pawn is weak, while Black has no way to get his hands on my
c3-pawn which is stabilising the whole construction.} Rd5 35. Rc6 Ke7 (35...
Ng5 {going for counterplay was interesting, but White wins a pawn and keeps it.
} 36. Rb6 Ne4 37. Nxb5 Ke7 38. Rb7+ Kf6 39. Na3 $1) 36. Rc7+ $6 {Too hasty.} (
36. Kf2 $1 {is how Karpov would play. I am still learning.}) 36... Kf6 37. Rb7
Nd6 38. Rd7 Rxd4 $2 {Counterplay was the right approach, but this is too
straightforward.} (38... Ke5 $1 {the king hurries towards d3.} 39. Kf1 (39.
Rxg7 Ke4 $1) (39. Re7+ Kf6 $1) 39... Ke4 40. Ke2 g5 {now if White moves the
rook from the d-file Black will get counterplay in the rook endgame with ...
Nf5!. For example:} 41. g3 (41. Rxh7 Kf4 $1 42. Rd7 Ne4 $1) 41... h5 42. Rh7
Nf5 43. Nxf5 Rxf5 44. Rxh5 Rf3 {and Black is in time to make a draw.}) 39. cxd4
Ke6 40. Rc7 Ne4 41. Kf1 Kd6 42. Rc8 Kd5 43. Rd8+ Kc6 44. d5+ (44. Ke2 {once
again bringing up the king first would be a good way to finish things off.}
Nc3+ 45. Kd2 Nd5 46. Rc8+ Kb6 47. Rh8 Nxb4 48. Rxh7 {and White will be first.})
44... Kc7 45. Re8 Nc3 46. Re7+ Kd6 47. Rxg7 Na2 48. Ke2 Nxb4 49. Rxh7 Nxd5 50.
h4 {In the pawn race the rook is clearly superior, but things soon got out of
hand.} b4 51. h5 (51. Kd2 $1 {would kill the counterplay, but it was somewhat
intuitive to let the pawns advance with checks.} b3 52. Kc1 c3 53. Rb7 b2+ 54.
Kb1) 51... b3 52. Rb7 $4 (52. Kd1 $1 {was still required, stopping the pawns.})
52... Nf4+ (52... Kc6 $1 {draws} 53. Rb8 Kc7 $1 {here we both hallucinated
that h6 was possible. Unfortunately, the knight is just in time to come back
to g6, so I would have to accede to a draw with Rxb3. This, fortunately,
didn't happen. Must be my guardian angel?}) 53. Ke3 Nxh5 $4 (53... Kc6 $1 {
still draws:} 54. Rb8 Kc7 $1) 54. Kd4 $2 (54. Rb5 $1 {wasn't easy, but it wins.
}) 54... Nf4 55. g4 Nd3 $4 (55... Nd5 $1 {was a miraculous draw. Now Black is
threatening to promote his c-pawn.}) 56. g5 Kc6 57. Rb8 $1 Kc7 58. Rb5 $1 {
Now it's over.} Nf4 59. Kxc4 Kd6 60. g6 Ne6 61. Rxb3 Ke7 62. Rf3 {A highly
tense game where in the end I could have played more strongly, to say the
least, but overall a good game and a grind I can be proud of!} 1-0

