[SourceQuality "1"]

{In the first game, we will see what happens when Black does not oppose
White's central expansion. As a rule, in such cases, White's space advantage
allows him to build a dangerous attack. Even though this was a blitz game,
Nakamura played in a very instructive way.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 e6 3. e4 h6 4.
Bxf6 Qxf6 5. c3 g6 6. Nd2 {This is a possible move order as well.} ({In
general, I prefer the more straightforward way of development} 6. Bd3 Bg7 7.
Ne2 {[%cal Gf2f4] and White is ready to proceed with f2-f4.}) 6... Bg7 7. Bd3
O-O 8. Ne2 d6 9. O-O a6 $6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7] Black does not fight for the
centre. Instead, he is planning to develop the light-squared bishop via b7. As
it will soon become clear, this is a wrong strategy.} ({Better is} 9... e5 10.
f4 Qe7 {which leads to a structure that will be dealt with in the next
examples.}) 10. f4 Qe7 11. Nf3 b5 12. e5 $1 {A key move in White's concept.
Besides seizing space in the centre, White is planning to exchange the
light-squared bishops via e4. On the other hand, the central pawn chain will
be restricting Black's dark-squared bishop.} Bb7 13. Ng3 Nd7 14. Be4 $1 {
This was the point behind White's previous play. The b7-bishop is Black's only
active piece. Conceptually speaking, after giving his dark-squared bishop for
the f6-knight, White is usually interested in exchanging the light-squared
bishops. Such an exchange fits into his light square strategy.} Bxe4 ({One of
the ideas behind 14.Be4 was to provoke the advance} 14... d5 $2 {[%csl Rb7]
when after} 15. Bd3 {[%cal Gg3e2,Gg2g4] followed by Ne2 and g2-g4, White has a
free attack on the kingside. Due to the closed centre, Black does not have
counterplay.}) 15. Nxe4 Nb6 16. Qd3 Nd5 17. g3 Rfd8 18. a4 {Even though his
long-term plan is based on a kingside attack, Nakamura creates queenside
targets as well.} Rab8 19. axb5 axb5 20. Rae1 Qe8 21. h4 $1 {[%cal Gh4h5]
Remember this thematic idea. In this structure, the threat of h4-h5 is very
annoying.} Qc6 {[%cal Gc6c4] Planning to parry White's attacking by exchanging
the queens via c4. This plan, however, is too slow.} 22. h5 Qc4 23. Qc2 gxh5
24. Nh4 $6 {This typical blitz move is an inaccuracy. Now, Black suddenly gets
decent chances. At the end of the day, however, Nakamura managed to win.} ({
White should have played} 24. Neg5 $1 hxg5 25. Nxg5 $18 {with a killing attack.
}) 24... b4 25. b3 Qc6 26. c4 Nc3 27. Nf6+ Bxf6 28. exf6 Ra8 29. f5 Ra2 30. Qd3
e5 31. dxe5 Qc5+ 32. Kh1 Qc6+ 33. Rf3 Rda8 34. e6 Ra1 35. Rxa1 Rxa1+ 36. Kh2
Qc5 37. Qe3 Ra2+ 38. Ng2 Qc6 39. exf7+ Kh7 40. f8=Q 1-0

