{This game shows White preventing f2-f4 by means of ...g7-g5 is not a good
idea.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 e6 3. e4 h6 4. Bxf6 Qxf6 5. c3 d6 6. Bd3 e5 7. Ne2 Nc6
$6 {This is not the most precise move for two reasons: 1) Black delays the
kingside development 2) The knight is not very flexible on c6} ({The best
continuation would be} 7... g6 8. O-O Bg7 {which will be examined in the next
examples.}) 8. O-O g5 $2 {This move is a big positional mistake. Black wants
to prevent f2-f4 at any price but weakens the entire complex of light squares.
White can now benefit from the f5-square in a very instructive way.} 9. Bb5 $1
{[%cal Gc8d7,Gd4d5] By pinning the knight, White provokes the exchange of the
light-squared bishops.} Bd7 (9... a6 {does not help either. After} 10. Qa4 {
Black should play ...Bd7 anyway.}) 10. d5 Nb8 11. Bxd7+ Nxd7 12. Ng3 $18 {
[%cal Gg3f5] After exchanging the light-squared bishops, White is going to
install a powerful knight on f5. The game is over.} h5 13. c4 O-O-O 14. Nc3 Be7
15. Nf5 Rdg8 16. b4 g4 17. a4 h4 18. a5 Rg5 19. a6 b5 20. Nxb5 Kb8 21. Qd3 h3
22. g3 Re8 23. Nc3 Rxf5 24. exf5 e4 25. Nxe4 Qxf5 26. Nc5 Qxd3 27. Nxd3 Bf6 28.
Rac1 Ne5 29. Nxe5 1-0

