{With this game, we start examining the most critical setup - Black fights for
a central space with ...e6-e5 and puts his bishop on g7.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 e6
3. e4 h6 4. Bxf6 Qxf6 5. c3 d6 6. Bd3 e5 7. Ne2 g6 8. O-O Bg7 9. f4 Qe7 {
This is the first critical position of the variation. Obviously, White's hopes
are based on a kingside attack. On the other hand, after consolidating on the
dark squares, in the long run, Black will try to make use of his bishop pair.
In order to further weaken the dark squares, he usually opts for the break ...
c7-c5. White has two main ways of handling the position: 1) gain space on the
kingside with f4-f5 2) keep the central tension Of course, both approaches
have advantages and drawbacks. We are going to discuss them in detail. In the
game, White played} 10. f5 {[%cal Gb1d2,Gd1b3,Gf1f2,Ga1f1] This move gives
White kingside space and puts pressure on the light squares. White usually
proceeds with Nd2 and Qb3, followed by doubling the rooks along the f-file. On
the downside, the advance f4-f5 decreases White's control over the dark
squares. In this game, Pantsulaia played} Nd7 $2 {This is a typical mistake
that you should now. Now, Black will not be able to castle.} ({The correct
continuation} 10... O-O {will be examined in the next example.}) 11. fxg6 fxg6
12. Nd2 Nf6 13. Qb3 $1 {This is the point. Now, there is no safe place for the
black king.} c6 {[%cal Gc8e6] Black is planning ...Be6 followed by 0-0.} 14.
Nc4 b5 ({It turns out that} 14... Be6 $2 {is impossible due to} 15. Qxb7 $18)
15. Ne3 $6 {This passive move lets Black get back into the game. Even though
White managed to win, the remaining part of the game is not that instructive.}
({White should have played} 15. Na5 $1 Bd7 16. a4 $18 {when Black's position
is hopeless. There is no safe place for his king.}) 15... Be6 16. d5 Bf7 17.
Qc2 a6 18. dxc6 Qa7 19. Rf3 Ng4 20. Qc1 h5 21. h3 Nf6 22. Kh1 Qc5 23. Qf1 Ke7
24. b4 Qxc6 25. Qf2 Be6 26. Rf1 Raf8 27. a4 bxa4 28. Qg3 Rh6 29. c4 a3 30. Qg5
a2 31. Nc3 Kd7 32. Nxa2 Nh7 33. Qg3 Rxf3 34. Rxf3 Qa4 35. Rf2 Bf6 36. Nd5 Bxd5
37. cxd5 Be7 38. Qe3 g5 39. Qa7+ Ke8 40. Bxa6 Qd1+ 41. Rf1 Qa4 42. Qb8+ 1-0

