{[%evp 0,80,38,14,29,-9,15,10,27,33,33,24,36,2,29,30,31,16,18,3,7,0,31,38,18,
18,26,-12,-16,7,7,-9,10,-48,-28,-56,-12,-94,-42,-197,-77,-100,-81,-90,-25,-117,
-78,-110,-142,-142,-134,-127,-125,-125,-125,-159,-126,-180,-141,-165,-131,-140,
-160,-153,-153,-153,-170,-191,-188,-212,-212,-212,-213,-200,-212,-211,-198,
-293,-327,-437,-439,-433,-343] After examining the most important structures
arising after 5.c3, we can now focus on some of the important alternatives.
After the moves} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 e6 3. e4 h6 4. Bxf6 Qxf6 {, the old main
line starts with} 5. Nc3 {[%cal Gd1d2,Ge1c1,Gf2f4] This move marks the
beginning of a very aggressive plan. White is planning to proceed with 6.Qd2
followed by 0-0-0 and f2-f4. The drawback is that the c2-pawn is now blocked
by the knight. Therefore, White does not have good control of the centre.
Black has at least two good setups against this plan. We will examine both. In
the current game, GM Nikolov opted for} d6 {which is the more positional
approach. Black wants to play ...c7-c6 followed by ...e6-e5, thus taking all
the important central squares under control. This plan is an easy to learn
good practical weapon.} 6. Qd2 c6 {[%csl Gd5][%cal Ge6e5] Before playing ...
e6-e5, Black must start with this move. It's really important to take the
e5-square under control.} 7. O-O-O e5 8. Nf3 {This natural move does not
challenge Black's setup.} ({White's best attempt in this structure is} 8. d5 {
[%cal Gg2g3,Gf2f4] with the idea to proceed with g2-g3 followed by f2-f4.} Nd7
9. g3 c5 10. f4 a6 11. Nf3 b5 $132 {[%cal Gh2h4,Gf1h3,Gg7g6,Gh6h5,Gf8h6,Gd7b6]
The position is very complicated. White will be trying to gain space on the
kingside and increase the pressure on e5. This idea can be achieved by means
of h2-h4 followed by Bh3. On the other hand, besides expanding on the
queenside, Black is planning to develop the bishop via h6.}) 8... Be7 9. h4 {
This move is pointless now since it only weakens the g4-square. White does not
have a kingside attack.} O-O 10. Be2 Bd8 {[%cal Gd8b6,Gb6a5] Remember this
thematic maneuver. By transferring the bishop to b6, Black wants to provoke
his opponent to release the central tension.} 11. Kb1 Bb6 {[%csl Rd4][%cal
Gc8g4] Black starts putting pressure on d4. In the near future, he can
consider playing ...Bg4 as well.} 12. Na4 $6 {The knight is not well place on
a4. Now, the advance ...b7-b5 is on the agenda.} Bc7 13. Rdg1 {[%cal Gg2g4,
Gg4g5] Planning to launch a kingside attack by means of g2-g4-g4. This plan is
slow and unrealistic. Momchil Nikolov immediately starts his queenside play -}
b5 14. dxe5 dxe5 {This is the pawn structure Black was hoping for. His plan is
rather simple - take the control of the d-file and start pushing the queenside
pawns. Additionally, the control of the key squares d4 and f4 is crucial.} 15.
Nc5 Rd8 16. Qe1 Qd6 17. Nd3 c5 {[%cal Gc5c4] Black acts according to the plan.
Now, ...c5-c4 is comming.} 18. g4 ({Taking the pawn with} 18. Ndxe5 $6 {
runs into} Qe7 19. Nd3 Nc6 {[%cal Gc5c4] with ...c5-c4 to follow. White's
position is hopeless.}) 18... c4 19. Nc1 g6 20. Qc3 Nc6 21. Rd1 Qc5 $17 {
Black already enjoys a big advantage. He managed to carry out his main
positional ideas. Later on, Nikolov brought the bacoon home.} 22. Rxd8+ Bxd8
23. g5 Ba5 24. Qe3 Qxe3 25. fxe3 hxg5 26. Nxg5 f6 27. Nf3 Be6 28. Nh2 Bb6 29.
h5 Kg7 30. Bg4 Bxg4 31. Nxg4 f5 32. h6+ Kf7 33. h7 Rh8 34. Nh6+ Kg7 35. exf5
Rxh7 36. f6+ Kf8 37. Rh3 Nd8 38. e4 Nf7 39. Nxf7 Rxh3 40. Nxe5 Rh1 0-1

