{[%evp 0,61,23,25,23,25,18,16,18,13,83,86,31,33,32,45,42,25,49,41,60,67,65,71,
61,60,67,39,64,69,68,65,89,98,87,118,115,83,121,118,118,94,186,145,129,88,88,
96,203,152,142,134,212,178,370,180,201,172,338,254,254,254,366,410] The
current example is a clear illustration of why the structures arising after 1.
d4 Nf6 2.Bg5 e6 3.e4 c5 4.d5 are favourable for White.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 ({
Of course, our classical move order starts with} 2. Bg5 {when after} e6 3. e4
c5 4. d5 h6 5. Bxf6 Qxf6 6. Nc3 {we transpose to the game.}) 2... e6 3. Bg5 c5
4. d5 h6 5. Bxf6 Qxf6 6. Nc3 {The d5-pawn is very annoying for Black. He
cannot put pressure against this pawn. White is planning to follow with e2-e4
and e4-e5, if allowed. Therefore, Black usually puts his central pawns on the
dark squares -} d6 7. e4 e5 {It's very important to understand how to handle
this structure. Contrary to the King's Indian Defence, in this structure, the
c4-square is available for the knight. White has the following classical plan
in such positions: 1) exchange the light-squared bishops 2) transfer the
f3-knight to c4 3) depending on the concrete circumstances break with either
b2-b4 or f2-f4 Black tries to apply the standard King's Indian plan based on ..
.f7-f5. With light-squared bishops exchanged, however, Black does not have
kingside attack.} 8. Bb5+ $1 {The most precise move. White invites the
exchange of the light-squared bishops after ...Bd7.} Bd7 9. a4 {This is a
multi-purpose move. Besides gaining space on the queenside, White is getting
ready to recapture with a pawn in response to the eventual ...Bxb5. In this
way, the a1-rook would immediately get into the game. Additionally, the
a4-pawn secures the c4-square for the knight since Black does not have ...
b7-b5.} Qd8 ({Another point behind 9.a4 can be seen after} 9... a6 $6 10. Bxd7+
Nxd7 11. a5 {[%csl Rb7][%cal Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Ga1b1,Gb2b4] White fixes the b7-pawn.
Later on, after the thematic Nd2-c4, White will proceed with Rb1 followed by
b2-b4.}) 10. O-O Be7 11. Nd2 O-O {[%cal Gd7c8]} 12. Bxd7 {Now, the exchange of
the bishops is needed. Otherwise, Black can keep his important bishop with ...
Bc8.} Nxd7 13. a5 {[%csl Gb6][%cal Gd2c4,Gd7b6,Ga5b6] Gaining further space
and taking the b6-square from the white knight.} g6 14. Nc4 Kg7 15. Qe2 Nf6 16.
g3 {[%cal Gf2f4] Since Black is very passive, Dubov decides to strike in the
centre with f2-f4.} Qd7 17. f4 exf4 18. gxf4 Rae8 19. Rad1 Nh5 20. e5 $18 {
Black's position is completely hopeless. White quickly converted his advantage.
} dxe5 21. fxe5 Bg5 22. Qf3 Bf4 23. Rde1 Qf5 24. Kh1 Qxc2 25. Re2 Qf5 26. Nd6
Qg5 27. Nxe8+ Rxe8 28. e6 f5 29. Rg2 Qh4 30. Ne2 g5 31. Nxf4 1-0

