{[%evp 0,25,23,23,23,-9,21,13,28,29,29,6,24,1,-5,2,8,6,6,8,3,3,11,10,21,32,32,
26] After} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 e6 3. e4 h6 4. Bxf6 Qxf6 5. c3 {Black can try to
obtain a French type of position by playing} d5 {I think that in this case,
White should keep the tension in the centre with the move} 6. Bd3 {The idea is
to recapture with the bishop whenever Black takes on e4. By doing so, the
white bishop will be putting pressure on the long diagonal. Therefore, in this
structure, White should keep the tension as long as possible.} c5 7. Nf3 Nc6 8.
O-O cxd4 {Black wants to provoke the formation of IQP. On the other hand,
White has now the opportunity to quickly develop his pieces.} ({Another
possibility is} 8... dxe4 9. Bxe4 Bd7 {Nevertheless, after} 10. Re1 {White is
already planning to open the position with d4-d5. Therefore, Black opt for a
quick development by means of} cxd4 11. cxd4 Bb4 12. Nc3 O-O {Now, White's
best chance is based on getting a position with semi-hanging pawns after} 13.
a3 Bxc3 14. bxc3 Rac8 15. Bc2 $13 {[%cal Gd1d3] planning to provoke kingside
weaknesses by means of Qd3. Whenever the black knight goes away from c6, White
can play Ne5. A rook-lift along the third rank comes into consideration as
well. Of course, the position is far from simple. If White does not manage to
organize serious play on the kingside, the vulnerability of the semi-hanging
pawns will tell in a the long run.}) 9. cxd4 dxe4 10. Bxe4 Bd6 11. Nc3 O-O ({
If Black wants to avoid structural damages by playing} 11... Bd7 {White can
open the position with} 12. d5 {White has an initiative.}) 12. Bxc6 $1 {
This exchange is one of the main points behind 6.Bd3. After} bxc6 13. Ne4 $14 {
White is slightly better. The c8-bishop remains passive for the time being. At
the same time, after exchanging the dark-squared bishop, White will make use
of the weak squares c5 and e5. The pressure on c6 can be annoying as well.} *

