{[%evp 0,43,23,26,26,26,21,13,13,10,14,14,14,6,16,1,14,-5,15,-9,-9,3,-7,-22,-7,
-26,3,4,16,8,14,7,30,18,55,51,65,57,73,56,40,128,120,120,304,279] If White
wants to play in a more positional way, instead of 3.e4 he can opt for a
London type of structure via different move orders. In such positions, the
control of the e5-square is of a crucial importance. The current game shows
how easily White can win by achieving a Stonewall type of structure.} 1. d4 Nf6
2. Nf3 ({Of course, our move order would be} 2. Bg5 e6 3. Nf3 ({Recently,
White started playing mostly} 3. Nd2 {which is considered to be the most
flexible approach. The idea is to keep the g1-knight flexible, In many cases
White can play Nf3 after the prior f2-f4. Additionally, if allowed, White can
play e2-e4 under favourable circumstances. For example, after} h6 4. Bh4 c5 {
, White's best move is} 5. e4 $1 {when the sequence} g5 6. Bg3 cxd4 7. e5 Nd5
8. h4 {leads to a position with good compensation for White.})) 2... e6 3. Bg5
d5 4. Nbd2 Be7 5. e3 O-O 6. Bd3 c5 7. c3 Nc6 8. O-O b6 {Black didn't play the
opening ambitiously and White has good control of the e5-square. Therefore,
Nisipeanu played} 9. Ne5 Bb7 10. f4 {Getting a favourable version of the
Stonewall structure is White's thematic idea in this line. Instead of being on
c1, the dark-squared bishop is participating in the attack. Black's position
is already very difficult. White is planning to proceed with the manoeuvre
Rf3-h3 or Qf3-h3.} h6 11. Bxf6 $1 {Eliminating the defender of the king is an
important idea in such structures. Now, the queen will land into h5.} Bxf6 12.
Qh5 {White is basically attacking for free since Black does not have any
counterplay. The next few moves are quite logical.} Bxe5 13. fxe5 Qg5 14. Qe2 {
[%cal Gf1f4,Ga1f1] White is ready to double the rooks on the f-file.} f5 15.
exf6 Rxf6 16. Rxf6 Qxf6 17. Rf1 Qe7 18. Qf3 $1 {Important prophylactic move.
White intends to meet ...Rf8 with Bh7+.} Rd8 19. h4 e5 $2 20. Qf5 e4 21. Nxe4
$1 dxe4 22. Bxe4 1-0

