{[#] Very often Black exchanges the e5-knight before White manages to play
f2-f4. This is how we might reach this pawn structure. Besides providing a lot
of space, the e5-pawn prevents black's pieces from joining the defence.
Therefore, Black usually plays ...f7-f6. As I explain in the next example, the
exchange of the e5-pawn does not solve Black's issues.}  *

[Event "Belgrade GMA op"]
[Site "Belgrade"]
[Date "1988.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Tseitlin, Mikhail S"]
[Black "Palac, Mladen"]
[Result "1-0"]
[ECO "D03"]
[WhiteElo "2455"]
[BlackElo "2335"]
[Annotator "GM Grigor Grigorov"]
[PlyCount "76"]
[EventDate "1988.12.??"]
[EventType "swiss"]
[EventRounds "9"]
[EventCountry "YUG"]
[SourceTitle "TD"]
[Source "ChessBase"]
[SourceDate "1994.03.01"]
[SourceVersion "1"]
[SourceVersionDate "1994.03.01"]
[SourceQuality "1"]

{Very often, Black exchanges the e5-knight without waiting for the advance
f2-f4. In this case, White recaptures with the d-pawn. This example is a good
illustration of White's attacking ideas in such positions.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Nf3 e6
3. Bg5 c5 4. e3 d5 5. Nbd2 Be7 6. c3 Nc6 7. Bd3 O-O 8. O-O b6 9. Ne5 {[%cal
Gf2f4]} Nxe5 10. dxe5 Nd7 {This is an important position. White should take a
decision regarding the exchange of the bishops. Strictly speaking, when we
have a space advantage, we should refrain from exchanging pieces. Therefore,
the move 11.Bf4 comes into consideration. In this case, however, White cannot
execute one of his main ideas - f2-f4. Additionally, the e5-pawn would need
constant protection. Therefore, White played} 11. Bxe7 Qxe7 12. f4 {[%cal
Gd1h5] Besides providing a space advantage, the e5-pawn prevents the
opponent's pieces to join the defence. That's why sooner or later Black will
have to play ...f7-f6. Palac did it immediately.} f6 13. Qh5 f5 $6 {This is
already a bit dubious decision. In such structures, the break g2-g4 is very
annoying for Black.} ({Better would have been} 13... g6 {when after} 14. Qh4 a5
{[%cal Gc8a6]} 15. exf6 Nxf6 {White should play} 16. Rae1 $1 {[%cal Ge3e4] A
very important moment. After the exchange exf6, White's main positional idea
is e3-e4. In such a case, Black does not have a favourable way to release the
central tension.}) 14. g4 Bb7 15. gxf5 exf5 16. Nf3 {The kingside pressure is
mounting. White is ready to proceed with Kf2 followed by Rg1.} g6 {You should
be always happy when you see this move on the board. Now, White has the
powerful idea of h2-h4-h5.} 17. Qh6 Rfd8 18. Kf2 {This is not a mistake but
now Black gets counterplay. Therefore, White needs to find many precise moves
in order to maintain the initiative. Not without some mistakes, White managed
to win.} ({Even more precise would have been} 18. h4 $1 Qg7 19. Qxg7+ Kxg7 20.
h5 Nf8 21. Kf2 Ne6 22. Rg1 $18 {White's attack is crushing.}) 18... d4 19. Bc4+
Kh8 20. Ng5 Nf6 21. Rg1 dxe3+ 22. Ke1 Ng8 23. Qh3 Bd5 24. Be2 h6 25. c4 Bc6 26.
Nf3 Qe6 27. Nh4 Be8 28. Bf3 Rac8 29. Bd5 Rxd5 30. cxd5 Qxd5 31. Qxe3 Ne7 32.
Kf2 Qe6 33. Rg3 Rd8 34. Kg1 Rd4 35. Nf3 Re4 36. Qd3 Nd5 37. Re1 Nxf4 38. Qd2
Rxe1+ 1-0

