{[%mdl 2] The moment has come to examine some examples in which Black refrains
from the advance ...d7-d5. Instead, he puts the pawn on d6, thus trying to
obtain some kind of Hedgehog setup.} 1. Nf3 Nf6 2. d4 e6 3. Bg5 {This game was
played in the last round and early in the morning. This move allows a
reduction in the time spent preparing for the opening and the chance to get a
playable position from the first moves.} c5 4. e3 cxd4 5. exd4 Be7 6. Bd3 b6 $1
{I think this is the most flexible and powerful placement for Black. A similar
system was used in the game Kamsky,G-Leko,P/Moscow 2008/0-1. Black is not
rushing to to close the pawn centre, preferring to develop all the pieces.} 7.
Nbd2 Bb7 (7... Ba6 $6 8. Bxf6 Bxf6 9. Bxa6 Nxa6 10. Ne4 Be7 11. d5 $36) 8. c3
d6 (8... O-O $6 9. Qc2 $5 h6 10. Bxf6 Bxf6 11. h4 $40) 9. Nf1 $5 {I made this
move after much thought. It looks unnatural, but this move allows me to keep
the tension. It is logical to look for other white moves:} (9. O-O O-O 10. Re1
{but here Black can exchange the bishops, which will simplify the game.} Nd5 $5
$11) 9... Nbd7 {Of course, now Black can't exchange the bishops, because I
have a retreat on d2.} (9... Nd5 10. Bd2) 10. Ng3 Qc7 11. Qe2 h6 12. Bd2 (12.
Bf4 $5 {Interesting move, provoking Black into active operations. But I
decided to act on the prearranged plan.} g5 $5 13. Bd2 g4 14. Nh4 O-O-O $13)
12... O-O 13. O-O Rfe8 14. Rae1 Bf8 {Black's pieces are located in successful
positions; the next pawn move e6-e5 is predictable.} 15. Qd1 e5 16. Nh4 $5 {
I needed to plan this move in advance. I think this position is equal, but I
was happy to get a position with a lot of pieces on the board! Our team needed
only a victory in this game!} exd4 {This move simplifies the position.} (16...
e4 $5 {looked more principled:} 17. Bb5 a6 18. Ba4 b5 19. Bc2 Nb6 20. Nhf5 (20.
f3 $5) 20... Nc4 21. Bc1 $132) 17. cxd4 a6 $6 {I find it hard to understand
this move. The most logical continuation of the past plan would be the
exchange of rooks:} (17... Rxe1 18. Rxe1 Re8 19. Rxe8 Nxe8 20. Nhf5 {The white
pieces are much more active, but creating an attack without rooks will be
difficult.}) 18. Nhf5 Qc6 $6 {I think it is also necessary to recognise that
this is a bad move. It was still not too late to exchange the major pieces,
though in a worse way.} (18... Rxe1 19. Rxe1 Re8 $14) 19. f3 {A simple and
strong move.} (19. Ne3 $4 Rxe3 $19) 19... d5 $2 {The completion of a very
unsuccessful phase of the game for Black. I suspect that my opponent initially
wanted to put the queen in the centre.} (19... Qd5 $2 20. Be4 $1 Nxe4 21. fxe4
Qe6 22. d5 Qg6 23. Nh5 $1 $18) (19... b5 $5 20. Bf4 Nd5 21. Qd2 $40) (19...
Rxe1 20. Qxe1 Re8 21. Qf2 $40) 20. Bf4 {Now all the white pieces come into
play, and Black can't exchange all of his rooks.} b5 (20... Rxe1 21. Qxe1 $1
Re8 22. Qd2 $36) 21. Qd2 {Up to a certain moment all White's moves look very
natural and logical. This position is pleasant for me in that I can play on
two flanks. Black should always be thinking about the sacrifice of pieces on
h6, and he should also be fearing the invasion of the white rook on the c-file.
} Rxe1 22. Rxe1 Re8 23. Rc1 Qb6 24. Kh1 {A normal prophylactic move, but I can
play more energetically:} (24. Bc7 $5 Qe6 25. Ba5 $1 {I did not see this
strong move.} Nb8 26. Bb4 $1 Bxb4 27. Qxb4 $16) 24... Re6 25. Ne2 {Maybe it's
not the strongest move, but it has a specific plan of attacking with the
g-pawn.} (25. Bc7 $5 Qa7 26. Ne2 Rc6 $5 27. Rxc6 Bxc6 28. Bd8 Qa8 29. Ne7+ Kh8
30. Nxc6 Qxc6 31. Qc2 Qb7 32. g3 $14) (25. Bxh6 $4 gxh6 26. Nxh6+ Bxh6 27. Qxh6
Ne4 $1 $19) 25... Rc6 26. Rg1 {The regrouping of forces was successful!} Re6 $1
{I blundered with this move.} 27. Qe1 {I am compelled to lose temp that can't
be good.} (27. g4 Ne4 $1 $132) (27. Rc1 Rc6) 27... b4 {The right decision.
Black wants to exchange the light-squared bishops.} 28. g4 {My plan comes into
action.} Nh7 $1 {A strong defensive resource.} (28... Ne4 $6 29. h4 $5 Nd6 30.
g5 $40) 29. Qg3 {This move is forcing the game, from now on forward only! It
was possible to return to positional play:} (29. h4 a5 30. Qd2 Ba6 31. Rc1 Bxd3
32. Qxd3 Rc6 33. Kg2 $14) 29... a5 30. Bc7 $5 {In mutual time trouble, I
decided to go on this difficult option. Direct attack leads only to a draw:} (
30. g5 $5 hxg5 31. Bxg5 (31. Nxg7 $5 Bxg7 32. Bxg5 Nxg5 33. Qxg5 Rg6 34. Bxg6
fxg6 35. Nf4 Nf8 $15) 31... Nxg5 32. Qxg5 (32. Nf4 $5 Ne4 $3 33. fxe4 dxe4 34.
Be2 e3+ 35. Bf3 Bxf3+ 36. Qxf3 Re8 37. Qg2 Qf6 $8 38. Nh5 Qg6 $1 39. Nfxg7 Bxg7
40. Nxg7 Qxg2+ 41. Rxg2 Re4 42. Nf5+ Kh7 43. Re2 Kg6 44. Nxe3 Rxd4 $11) 32...
Rg6 33. Ne7+ Bxe7 34. Qxe7 Rxg1+ 35. Kxg1 Ba6 $5 36. Bxa6 Qxa6 $11) 30... Qc6 (
30... Qa7 $2 31. Nf4 Rc6 32. Bd8 Qb8 33. Be7 $16) 31. Rc1 Qa4 $132 {
Unexpectedly the black queen becomes more active on the edge of the board.} 32.
Bd6 $1 {The right move. I am ready to give up pawns on the queenside, but my
rook is beginning to create dangerous threats.} Qxa2 33. Rc7 {I can't blame
myself for this move. It was hard to find the strong prophylactic move:} (33.
Ng1 $3 {The game continues, White's chances are a little higher.}) 33... Qxb2
$2 {This move can't be called a big mistake considering the major time
pressure. Black can force a draw in this version:} (33... Qb3 $1 34. f4 $8 Qxb2
35. Rxd7 Rxe2 36. Bxe2 Qxe2 37. Rxb7 Qf1+ 38. Qg1 Qf3+ 39. Qg2 Qd1+ 40. Qg1 $11
) 34. Ng1 $1 {Now, this move seems logical. The white king feels comfortable
and Black must seek protection against many threats.} (34. Rxd7 $2 Rxe2 35.
Bxe2 Qxe2 36. Rxb7 Qf1+ 37. Qg1 Qxf3+ 38. Qg2 Qd1+ 39. Qg1 $11) 34... Qd2 $2 {
A crucial mistake.} ({After} 34... Bxd6 35. Nxd6 Nhf8 $5 36. Rxb7 Qxd4 37. Bf5
Re7 38. Nc8 $1 Re8 39. Bxd7 Nxd7 40. Nd6 Rd8 41. Nf5 $14 {the game continues.})
35. Rxd7 $18 {The black king becomes my main goal!} Bc6 (35... Qxd3 36. Bxf8
Nxf8 37. Rxf7 $1 Rg6 (37... Kxf7 38. Qc7+ Ke8 39. Nxg7#) 38. Rxb7 $18) (35...
Nf6 36. Rd8 Re8 37. Rxe8 Nxe8 38. Bxf8 Qxd3 39. Qe5 $1 $18) 36. Rd8 Qxd3 (36...
Be8 37. Ne7+ Bxe7 38. Rxe8+ Bf8 39. Bxh7+ Kxh7 40. Rxe6 fxe6 41. Bxf8 b3 42.
Qe5 Qg5 43. Qxg5 hxg5 44. Ba3 $18) 37. Bxf8 Nxf8 38. Qb8 $1 {Perhaps my
opponent somehow didn't see this long move.} Re1 (38... Be8 39. Rxe8 Rxe8 40.
Qxe8 b3 41. Ne7+ Kh7 42. Qxf8 $18) 39. Rxf8+ Kh7 40. Rh8+ Kg6 41. Qf4 1-0

