{[%evp 0,110,18,26,21,7,25,4,4,4,6,4,29,31,29,28,26,18,28,13,11,7,12,7,13,1,7,
-12,-2,-6,-1,-7,-29,-31,-24,-27,13,22,13,12,19,30,12,23,21,25,22,-7,50,38,28,
38,15,70,78,64,65,76,76,63,57,51,57,39,50,42,45,45,45,55,57,50,57,40,42,13,21,
50,52,21,50,30,42,32,35,40,43,15,24,30,25,14,6,15,15,18,22,22,16,28,16,10,27,
16,20,21,20,20,20,20,12,10,10] A completely different position would arise if
Black develops his knight to c6 instead of d7. A very instructive example is
the game Kasimdzhanov - Spasov.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 e6 3. Nd2 c5 4. e3 cxd4 5.
exd4 Be7 6. Ngf3 b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O O-O 9. Re1 Nc6 10. c3 {This is the main
tabiya of the variation. White has good central control and harmoniously
developed pieces. His main idea is to create queenside weaknesses by means of
a2-a4-a5. Additionally, the c6-knight is highly restricted. That's why Black
usually plays} Nd5 11. Bxe7 Ncxe7 12. Bf1 $1 {The best square for the bishop
in this pawn structure. White practically neutralizes the potential pressure
on g2 after a move like ...Nf4.} Nf6 13. a4 $1 {[%cal Ga4a5] White is now
ready to start his typical queenside plan.The advance a4-a5 is already on the
agenda.} Rb8 {Black anticipates the advance a4-a5. Potentially, the rook will
be putting pressure on b2.} 14. Ne5 Qc7 15. a5 bxa5 16. Qa4 Bc6 {[%cal Gb8b2]
This was the point behind ...Rb8. White cannot immediately take the pawn. On
the other hand, however, the black pawn will not run away.} 17. Qa3 Ng6 18.
Nxc6 Qxc6 19. g3 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Gg6f4,Gg6h4,Ge1b1,Ga3a5] Prophylactic among
everything! Before start playing against the a5-pawn, White restricts Black's
possible kingside counterplay.} a4 20. Reb1 Rb7 21. Nc4 $6 {This is not the
precise way to handle the position.} ({White should have played} 21. Qxa4 Qxa4
22. Rxa4 Rfb8 23. b4 $16 {with a stable advantage.}) 21... Qc7 22. Qxa4 Rfb8
23. Qa3 Rb3 24. Qc5 Qxc5 25. dxc5 Ne4 26. c6 dxc6 27. Re1 Nf6 28. Rxa7 Nd5 29.
Ra2 Nge7 30. Re2 g6 31. Rc2 c5 32. Ra5 R3b5 33. Ra6 R5b7 34. Bg2 Kg7 35. Rd2
Rc7 36. Kf1 Rbb7 37. Nd6 Rb8 38. Nc4 Rbb7 39. Nd6 Rb8 40. Ke1 h5 41. h4 Nf6 42.
Nc4 Ned5 43. Ne5 Nb6 44. Kd1 Nfd5 45. Bf1 Kf6 46. Nc4 Nxc4 47. Bxc4 Nb6 48. Be2
Ke7 49. Kc1 Nd7 50. Ra4 Nb6 51. Ra5 Nd7 52. Kc2 Rcb7 53. Kb1 Rc7 54. Kc2 Rcb7
55. Kb1 Rc7 1/2-1/2

