{[%evp 0,75,21,19,28,7,44,-3,-3,-10,13,3,10,3,5,7,7,10,10,10,10,17,9,8,9,11,14,
17,21,32,44,48,63,66,70,84,90,78,68,85,86,75,72,56,165,98,96,77,82,68,50,49,73,
59,59,40,42,48,63,58,58,0,99,65,71,74,64,82,109,104,125,125,128,124,122,122,
130,134] Before I start the lecture, I would like to share with you my
thoughts about Trompowsky Attack. I think it is just a powerful weapon to play
for a win and the statistic of high-level games prove it. I have more than 20
years experience with Trompowsky and this opening brings me a lot of important
wins over the years. I am starting with one of my games against the IM Dimitar
Dochev from Bulgaria.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 g6 $6 {I always liked to play against
this move, because I think that I feel the structure and the arising positions
very well. After such move you should take the knight. In general in
Trompowksy Attack in almost all the lines, you should be ready to give up your
bishop for the enemies knight.} 3. Bxf6 exf6 4. e3 (4. c4 {It is also possible
to start with this move}) 4... Bg7 (4... d5 {Is another possibility for Black
and is discussed in the next game (Bosiocic - Jaracz)}) 5. c4 f5 {It is not
easy for Black to activate and use his bishop pair, with 8 pawns on the board,
it is inevitable that one of the bishops will be weak.  White's plan is
straightforward. Since we exchange our dark-squared bishop, we want to put
most of our pawns on the dark-squares. For example: d4,e3,f2,g3,h2 (or h4).
One move which we should try to avoid at any cost is the move d4-d5. This will
block the "d5" square and will open Black's "g7" bishop.} 6. Nc3 O-O 7. Nge2 $1
{The first important moment of the game. It is crucial to start with this move
instead of the most popular 7.g3.} (7. g3 $6 {Looks logical, but allows a
powerful reply.} c5 $1 8. dxc5 ({If White tries to keep the structure, then
Black proceeds with} 8. Nge2 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nc6 10. Ndb5 d6 (10... d5 $146 {
this blow is also very powerful} 11. Nxd5 (11. cxd5 a6 12. dxc6 axb5 13. Qxd8
Rxd8 14. Bxb5 bxc6 15. Bxc6 Rb8 {[%csl Rb2,Rc3] Black is two pawns down, but
the powerful bishops and the pressure on the queenside promise him at least
equal chances.}) 11... Bxb2 12. Rb1 Be5 13. Bg2 a6 {and again I would prefer
to play this position with Black pieces}) 11. Nxd6 (11. Qxd6 Qa5 $44) (11. Bg2
Be6 {[%csl Rc4][%cal Re6c4]}) 11... Be6 {With more than enough compensation
for the sacrificing material.}) 8... Bxc3+ $1 9. bxc3 Qa5 {I would prefer
Black here.}) 7... d6 (7... c5 $6 {Now this strike is not so strong, because
White can simply meet it with} 8. dxc5 $1 {[%csl Rc3][%cal Re2c3]} Qa5 9. Rc1 {
[%csl Rc3][%cal Rc1c3]} Qxc5 10. Nf4 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rf4d5,Rc3d5]} b6 11. Be2
Bb7 12. O-O {[%csl Rd5,Rd7] The arising position is the dream for White in
this opening. White has better structure and full control of the important
"d5" square.}) (7... b6 {was tried in a couple of games, but doesn't promise
Black equality after:} 8. Nf4 Bb7 9. Be2 $1 {an important maneuver to exchange
the light-squared bishop.} d6 ({The aggresive} 9... g5 {is not working well
for Black after} 10. Nh5 Bxg2 11. Rg1 Bb7 12. Qc2 {[%csl Rf5][%cal Rc2f5]
Black's kingside will collapse soon.}) 10. Bf3 Qc8 11. O-O Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Nd7
13. Qc6 Rb8 14. Nfd5) 8. g3 Nd7 (8... Be6 {[%cal Re6c4] is well met by} 9. Bg2
c6 10. Qd3 $14) 9. Bg2 Nf6 10. O-O Re8 {[%csl Re4,Rg2][%cal Rf6e4]} (10... Qe7
{GM Peter Svidler himself tried this move, but in my opinion is just bad. In
such position, White is trying to exchange a pair of knights. In this case
Black will be very passive and without any counterplay.} 11. Nd5 $1 Nxd5 (11...
Qd8 {is the best reply, but it is not easy to play such a move and to admit
that you were wrong.} 12. Nxf6+ Qxf6 13. b4 $14 {[%csl Rb7,Rg2][%cal Rb4b5,
Ra2a6] With an initiative on the queenside.}) 12. cxd5 $1 {[%csl Rc7,Rd4][%cal
Rg7d4] In my opinion, this position is strategically lost. Black's
dark-squared bishop is in "theory" good, but practically passive and in a
"cage". White's plan is straightforward, just triple his major pieces on the
semi-open c-file and attack the backward "c7" pawn.}) 11. Qd3 {White has a
choice between Qc2 or Qd3, in my opinion, the latest is the better square.} c6
(11... Qe7 {again this is met by} 12. Nd5 {[%cal Rd5f6,Rf6d5]} Nxd5 13. cxd5 {
[%csl Rc7][%cal Ra1c1,Rc1c3,Rf1c1]}) 12. b4 Qe7 13. b5 Ne4 (13... Bd7 {I faced
this move very often in my practice. White should increase the pressure on the
queenside by means of 14.Rab1 or 14.a4. In all my games, I played 14.Rab1. b
For my surprise,when I checked with the engine, it appears that this move is
not very accurate, because it allows a tactical trick.} 14. a4 $1 (14. Rab1 $6
f4 $1 (14... Ne4 {is simply bad due to} 15. bxc6 bxc6 (15... Bxc6 16. Nf4 $14 (
16. d5 $2 Nc5 $11 {[%cal Rc5b7,Rc6d7]})) 16. Rb7 $16 {[%csl Re4][%cal Rb7d7,
Rd7e7,Rc3e4,Rd3e4,Rg2e4]}) (14... Rab8 $6 {This move is well met by the
typical Rb3 with the intention to double on the b-file.} 15. Rb3 {[%csl Rb7,
Rb8][%cal Rf1b1,Rb5c6]}) 15. Nxf4 Bf5 16. Qd2 Bxb1 17. Rxb1 Rac8 {White
probably has enough compensation for the exchange, but definitely not more
than that.}) 14... Ne4 15. Rfb1 Rac8 16. a5 h5 17. h4 $16 {White stops any
kind of counterplay on the kingside and is ready to proceed with a6 or bxc6
next.} (17. bxc6 {is also possible} Bxc6 18. Bxe4 fxe4 19. Qd1 h4 20. Nf4 {
[%cal Rf4d5,Rc3d5]} Bh6 21. Qg4 $14)) 14. Rab1 h5 15. h4 Bd7 16. bxc6 bxc6 (
16... Bxc6 {If there is no pawn on c6, White always employs the plan of
putting the knight on "d5" by means of} 17. Nf4 $16) 17. Rb7 Nxc3 18. Nxc3 Rec8
19. Rfb1 Qe8 20. Qd1 (20. Ne2 $5 {[%cal Re2d4,Re2f4,Rd3b3] This was probably
more accurate. Stopping any hopes for counterplay on the kingside and
preparing Qa3.}) 20... Qd8 21. Qa4 a5 (21... f4 {was the last chance for an
active play.} 22. exf4 Bxd4 23. Nd5 Kg7 24. Qd1 c5 (24... Bc5 25. Nc3 Bf5 26.
Be4 $16)) 22. Qa3 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Ra3d6]} Bf8 (22... Be6 {is well met by} 23.
d5 cxd5 24. Nxd5 Rxc4 25. Qd3 Rc5 26. Nb6 Rb8 27. Rxb8 Qxb8 28. Na4 $16 {
[%cal Ra4c5,Rb1b8]}) 23. Na4 Rc7 24. Rxc7 (24. R7b6) 24... Qxc7 25. Qb3 Kg7 26.
Qb7 {After exchanging the queens, Black's queenside collapsed.} Ra7 27. Qxc7
Rxc7 28. Rb8 Be7 29. Nb6 Be6 30. a4 (30. f4 {[%csl Re6,Rf5]}) 30... Kf6 31. f4
{Typical move for this structure, which locks the kinside completely.} Kg7 32.
Kf2 Bf6 33. Ke2 Be7 34. Kd3 Bf6 35. Na8 Rc8 36. Rxc8 Bxc8 37. Bxc6 {Finally
White wins a pawn and the endgame is hopeless for Black.} Bd8 38. c5 {I found
this game very instructive. As you can see, my opponent lost without posing
any single threat. Those kinds of positional wins are my favorite. Few bullet
points to remember from this game are: 1. Move order is important - start with
7.Nge2 2. Try to put most of your pawns on dark squares and never push d4-d5.
3. White's queen is better placed on d3 than on c2 4. In most of the cases
where Black didn't play Ne4, you should start with a4, instead of Rab1} 1-0

