{[%evp 0,57,21,19,28,0,2,0,43,-1,-9,-8,23,23,34,30,33,30,30,27,70,66,157,105,
92,91,140,153,135,101,122,88,85,85,215,51,314,182,516,171,159,245,580,231,270,
105,222,140,286,276,480,335,1205,2215,2455,29982,29983,29984,29985,29986]} 1.
d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. e3 g6 4. Bxf6 exf6 {This position can be reached by
another move order as well - 2...g6.} 5. c4 dxc4 (5... c6 $6 {This move is
just innacurate. All the time when you see c6 you should continue with:} 6.
cxd5 $1 Qxd5 (6... cxd5 $16 {[%csl Rd5] This position is close to lost,
because Black can't defend the "d5" pawn. White has three minor pieces which
can attack this pawn and Black has only two, because his darksquared bishop
can't defend it.} 7. Nc3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rf1g2,Rg2g3,Rg1e2,Re2f4,Rd1b3,Rb3d5]}
Nc6 8. Qb3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rb3d5]} Be6 (8... Na5 $2 9. Bb5+ Bd7 10. Qxd5 $18)
(8... Bb4 9. a3 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 $16) 9. Qxb7 $18) 7. Nc3 Bb4 8. a3 $1 {I think
White should challenge the bishop immediately} Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 O-O 10. c4 Qd6 11.
Bd3 {[%csl Rc4,Rd4,Re3,Rf6,Rf7]} Nd7 12. Ne2 {one thing to remember is that
the knight is usually better placed on "e2" in this structure, because on "f3"
it would be restricted by the "f6" pawn.} b6 13. O-O Bb7 14. a4 Rfd8 15. a5 $16
) 6. Bxc4 Bg7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Nge2 f5 9. h4 {Typical move in this structure.
White delays castling and starts an attack against Black's king. In fact Black
can't really stop the advance "h4-h5". In my opinion the more accurate move
order is to start with 9.Qc2.} (9. Qc2 $1 {and if} c6 {then} (9... c5 $5 {
can be met by} 10. dxc5 Nd7 11. Nf4 Nxc5 12. Rd1 Qa5 13. O-O Bd7 14. Ncd5 $16 {
with a big positional advantage for White.}) 10. h4 $1 {with a big advantage.})
9... c6 (9... c5 $3 {Black should follow the old principle - flang attack
should be met with strike in the centre.} 10. h5 (10. dxc5 Nd7 {[%cal Rd7c5]}
11. Qc2 Nxc5 {with a good game for Black. With such open centre the advance
h4-h5 is not so dangerous anymore.}) 10... cxd4 11. hxg6 (11. Nxd4 {is always
met by Nd7} Nd7) 11... hxg6 12. Nxd4 Nd7 $1 (12... Nc6 $6 {I think that "d7"
is better square for the kngiht. I am giving you some illustrative lines.} 13.
Nxc6 bxc6 14. Qxd8 (14. Qf3 Qb6 15. Qh3 Re8 {[%csl Rg7][%cal Rg8f8] and Black
is fine}) 14... Rxd8 15. Rc1 Bb7 16. Ke2 c5 17. f3 $14 {[%csl Rc5]}) 13. Qb3
Nb6 14. O-O-O Nxc4 15. Qxc4 Qe7 16. Nd5 Qe5) (9... h5 $2 {is an amateur move
after which White has big advantage. One illustrative variation is:} 10. Nf4 {
[%cal Rf4g6,Rf4h5]} Kh7 11. Qb3 {[%cal Rb3f7,Rb3b7]} Qe7 12. Ncd5 Qd6 13. Qa3 {
[%csl Rc7][%cal Ra3d6]} Qxa3 14. bxa3 $16 {[%csl Rc7][%cal Rd5c7]}) 10. h5 Qe7
11. hxg6 hxg6 12. Nf4 {[%csl Rg6][%cal Rf4g6,Rc4g8]} Qd6 13. Qf3 {[%cal Rf3h3,
Rh3h7]} Nd7 14. Qh3 (14. O-O-O $1 {I would prefer this move after which
White's attack is simply unstoppable.} Nb6 15. Bb3 $16 {[%cal Rf3d5,Rb3d5,
Rc3d5,Rf4d5,Rf4g6,Rc1b1]}) 14... Re8 15. O-O-O b5 16. Bb3 a5 17. d5 $4 {
strange mistake, but a very instructive one - you should never play d4-d5 in
this structure.} (17. Qh7+ $1 {was easy winning.} Kf8 18. Rh6 $1 Bxh6 (18... a4
19. Nxg6+ fxg6 20. Qg8+ Ke7 21. Qxg7+ Kd8 22. Rxg6 $18) 19. Qxf7#) 17... c5 (
17... Nc5 $1 18. dxc6 Nxb3+ 19. axb3 Qxc6 $17 {[%csl Rg8]}) 18. Nxb5 {After
some complication and mutual mistakes White manages to win this game. The rest
of it is not important for our topic, so I leave it without comments.} Qb6 19.
d6 c4 20. Bxc4 Ne5 21. Be2 Bd7 22. Rd5 Bxb5 23. Bxb5 Rac8+ 24. Kb1 Red8 25.
Rxe5 Bxe5 26. Qh7+ Kf8 27. Nxg6+ fxg6 28. Qe7+ Kg8 29. Qxe5 {[%csl Rh8][%cal
Rh1h8]} 1-0

