{[%evp 0,117,21,19,28,0,2,0,43,-1,-1,-42,-7,-16,20,20,15,20,24,18,17,17,18,18,
22,-1,5,-2,3,-6,-3,-11,-7,1,35,2,32,43,56,56,65,88,87,90,85,104,95,99,108,94,
91,95,86,82,67,60,60,74,74,25,71,75,70,6,89,-17,139,139,145,153,147,147,175,
162,162,186,181,193,186,163,162,170,166,161,161,161,159,154,158,143,130,120,
152,141,151,152,152,137,179,164,171,168,232,200,188,171,222,233,231,225,236,
198,200,198,381,386,418,422,442,444]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. e3 g6 4. Bxf6 exf6
5. g3 {In this game we will see another possible idea for Black. He delays the
move c4 for a while and first develop his kinside. After developing the bihsop
to "g2" he prepares c4 by means of Nd2.} c6 6. Nd2 f5 7. Bg2 Nd7 8. Ne2 Nf6 9.
O-O Bd6 10. c4 dxc4 ({If Black decides to protect d5 with} 10... Be6 {White
should continue} 11. c5 $1 {winning space on the queenside.} Bc7 12. b4 O-O 13.
a4 Ne4 14. Qc2 {Black's only chance is to organize an attack on the kingside,
but as we see it is not so easy.} h5 {is always well met by} (14... g5 15. b5
h5 16. f3 (16. Nf3 h4 (16... g4 17. Nh4)) 16... Nxd2 17. Qxd2 Kg7 18. f4 {
[%csl Rb7,Rd5,Re6,Rf5][%cal Ra1b1,Rb1b7]}) 15. h4 $1 g5 (15... f6 $6 {is not
very good here due to} 16. Nf3 g5 17. hxg5 fxg5 18. Ne5 Qf6 (18... g4 19. Nf4
Qe8 20. b5 $18) 19. f3 {and White is winning a piece.}) 16. hxg5 Qxg5 {Black
activates the queen, but his structure is damaged.} 17. Nf3 Qh6 18. Nf4 {
White knights control everything on the kingside.}) 11. Nxc4 Bc7 12. b4 $1 {
as in my game against Dochev, White plans to prepare the advance "b4-b5". This
will open White's light square bishop and will put pressure on the queenside.}
O-O 13. a4 Be6 14. Qc2 a6 (14... Bd5 {Is a good try, but I think that White
keeps an advantage after:} 15. Bxd5 Qxd5 16. Rfc1 Ne4 17. Nf4 Bxf4 18. gxf4 Qe6
19. Ne5 a6 20. Qb2 $14) 15. Rfc1 Qe7 16. Rab1 Bd5 17. b5 Bxg2 (17... cxb5 {
This doesn't help} 18. axb5 a5 19. Bxd5 Nxd5 20. b6 Bb8 21. Rb5 Qd7 22. Rxa5
$18) 18. Kxg2 cxb5 19. axb5 axb5 (19... a5 20. b6 Bd6 21. Nxd6 Qxd6 22. Qc5 $16
) 20. Rxb5 $16 {White is much better. As you see, White has a protected passed
pawn on the "d" file, and the pawn on "b7" most likely will fall.} Ra7 21. Qb3
Qd7 22. Kg1 Rb8 23. Nc3 h5 24. Nd2 (24. Ne5 $1 Bxe5 25. dxe5 Ne4 26. Nd5 $18 {
[%cal Rd5f6,Rf2f3]}) 24... h4 25. Nf3 hxg3 26. hxg3 Kg7 27. Nd5 Nxd5 28. Rxd5
Qe7 29. Qb5 Bd6 30. Ne5 Rba8 31. Kg2 Ra1 32. Rc2 (32. Rxa1 Rxa1 33. Qd7) 32...
Rh8 (32... Qg5 $1 {Was an excellent chance for Black which Cheparinov missed.
It was a blitz game, so probably both players were in time trouble.} 33. Rxd6
Qh5) 33. Qd7 Qxd7 34. Nxd7 Be7 35. Rc7 $18 {The endgame is just hopeless for
Black and White converts it easily.} Rd8 36. Rxb7 Ra6 37. Rdb5 Re6 38. Ne5 Rf8
39. Rd7 Bf6 40. Nd3 Re7 41. Rbb7 Rxd7 42. Rxd7 Ra8 43. Nc5 Kg8 44. Nb7 Ra7 45.
Kf3 Kg7 46. Nc5 Ra2 47. Ne6+ Kg8 48. Nf4 Ra8 49. Nd5 Bg5 50. g4 Kg7 51. gxf5
gxf5 52. Nf4 Kf6 53. Rd6+ Kg7 54. Nh5+ Kh7 55. Rc6 Ra5 56. Rc5 Rxc5 57. dxc5
Kg6 58. c6 Bd8 59. Nf4+ 1-0

