{[%evp 0,41,21,19,28,8,11,13,13,-8,-10,-16,4,4,4,4,4,13,13,-13,8,1,35,14,18,18,
20,15,24,-51,47,44,49,79,70,65,109,109,119,411,727,728,811,867]} 1. d4 Nf6 2.
Bg5 c5 3. Bxf6 gxf6 (3... exf6 4. Nc3 $1 {I like this move a lot.} cxd4 5. Qxd4
Nc6 6. Qe4+ $1 {White is better after this move.} Be7 7. e3 O-O 8. Bc4 Re8 9.
Nge2 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Re2c3,Rc3d5] The main problem for Black is the square
"d5", White is in total control.}) 4. d5 Qb6 5. Qc1 f5 6. c4 Bg7 7. Nc3 d6 (
7... Qg6 {is well met by the tricky} 8. h4 $1 h5 9. Nh3) 8. e3 Nd7 {[%csl Rd7,
Rf1]} 9. Qc2 $1 {A clever waiting move. White wait for Black to determine the
place of his knight and then will develop his pieces on kingside. White's plan
is to met Ne5 with Be2 and Nh3 and Nf6 with Bd3 and Nge2.} Nf6 (9... Ne5 10.
Nh3 Bd7 11. Be2 O-O-O (11... O-O 12. Nf4 Ng6 13. Nh5 Bh8 14. f4 {[%csl Rf5]
[%cal Re3f4] fixing the weakness on the kingside.} e6 {and planning to open
the game with g2-g4.} 15. g4 $1 $40) 12. Nf4 {[%cal Ra1b1,Rb2b4,Ra2a3] with
the idea to open the queenside with b2-b4.}) 10. Bd3 e6 (10... Ne4 {was the
main theory 20 years ago.} 11. Nge2 Nxc3 12. bxc3 $1 {This is a nice concept.
White wants to keep the knight on the kingside.} e6 13. O-O O-O 14. Ng3 Bd7 15.
f4 Rae8 16. e4 fxe4 17. Bxe4 f5 {is well met by} 18. dxe6 Bxe6 19. Bxf5 $18)
11. Nge2 Bd7 12. O-O O-O-O (12... O-O {against short castle we have two
possible plans.} 13. dxe6 (13. Rad1 Rae8 14. dxe6 (14. Rd2 {[%csl Rd6][%cal
Rf1d1,Rd1d6]} Kh8 15. Rfd1 Qd8 16. dxe6 fxe6 17. Nf4 $16) (14. Ng3 {is also
possible} a6 15. f4 $16) 14... fxe6 15. e4 fxe4 16. Nxe4 Nxe4 17. Bxe4 h6 18.
Rd2 $16 {[%csl Rd6][%cal Rf1d1]}) 13... fxe6 14. e4 fxe4 15. Nxe4 {with an
attack}) 13. Rab1 Rhg8 {I have three games in this position, I won 2 but lost
the most important one against GM Iotov which was decisive for the title in
the Bulgarian Individual Championship. I lost that game because I didn't play
the most natural move b2-b4! I analyze this loss carefully, learn the
subtleties of the position and then won two nice games in this position.} 14.
b4 $3 cxb4 (14... Kb8 15. Rb3 Bc8 16. bxc5 Qxc5 17. Nd4 $18) 15. a3 Kb8 16.
Rxb4 $1 {We need to take with the rook on b4, the attack on the semi-open file
is more important than the pawn structure.} Qc5 17. Rfb1 Bc8 18. Nd4 {[%cal
Rd4c6]} Ka8 19. Na4 Qc7 20. Nb6+ $1 {nice blow} Kb8 (20... axb6 21. Nb5 $18 {
[%cal Rc2a4,Ra4a7]}) 21. Nc6+ bxc6 22. Nd7+ Ka8 23. Rb8+ Qxb8 24. Rxb8# {
Nice attacking game.} 1-0

