{[%evp 0,21,51,31,18,-9,-6,-24,-7,-4,-12,-18,-12,3,9,-25,-9,-28,-18,-16,-10,
-35,16,35] In this game I will show you a plan which usually works against not
very experienced opponents. The plan is to wait for Black to castle short and
play Qf3 followed by advancing "h" and "g" pawns on the kingside. The drawback
of this idea is that Black can play an early "f6-f5" and then simply met Qf3
with g6. Then White's idea simply doesn't work.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6
exf6 4. e3 c6 5. Bd3 Bd6 (5... Qb6 6. b3 {[%csl Rb1,Rb6][%cal Rc2c4]}) 6. Nd2
O-O (6... f5 $1 {stopping Qf3}) 7. Qf3 $1 {[%cal Rg2g4,Rh2h4] now Black can't
play f5 and White is simply better.} Na6 {[%cal Ra6b4,Ra6c7,Rc6c5]} (7... Qb6 {
is possible way of development, but White can simply castle} 8. O-O-O $16) (
7... g6 8. g4 $1 $16 {[%cal Rg1e2,Rh2h5]}) 8. c3 Nc7 ({an immediate} 8... c5 {
is not possible, because the pawn is hanging} 9. Qxd5 $18) 9. Ne2 g6 10. g4 $1
{You should remember that g6 is always met by g4!} c5 {against c5, we can
change the plan and play against the isolated pawn on "d5"} ({after a neutral
move, White can proceed with his plan.} 10... Re8 11. h4 $1 Be6 12. h5 g5 {
opening the "h" file, can't be good for Black} 13. h6 $1 a5 14. Nf1 {The
knight is heading to h5 or f5.} a4 15. Nfg3 $18 {[%cal Rg3h5,Rh5f6]}) 11. dxc5
Bxc5 12. h4 b5 13. h5 Ne6 14. Nf4 Nxf4 15. Qxf4 b4 ({it was probably better to
play} 15... g5 16. Qf3 {[%csl Rd5][%cal Rd3b5,Re1c1]} b4 17. c4 Bb7 (17... Be6
18. cxd5 Qxd5 19. Be4 $18) 18. Qf5 $18) 16. Qh6 Qc7 17. hxg6 fxg6 18. Bxg6 {
A crushing win for the young Mamedyarov against a strong opponent.} 1-0

