{[%evp 0,137,19,31,43,3,30,14,11,-14,-12,-10,-9,3,55,25,41,41,28,36,30,18,12,
12,13,19,21,29,21,15,0,0,21,29,9,8,-14,-21,-29,-37,-33,-66,-32,-110,-35,-120,
86,96,100,87,69,65,65,63,80,46,74,45,24,33,49,53,59,65,56,53,56,56,58,52,52,18,
47,51,58,38,65,17,12,45,41,-12,-6,-95,-85,-105,-92,-94,-94,-109,-94,-95,-80,
-81,-78,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-71,-81,
-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,
-95,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-81,-70,-81]} 1. d4 d5 2. Bg5 c6 3. e3 Nf6 4. Bxf6 exf6
5. Bd3 Bd6 6. Nd2 ({this time} 6. Qf3 $6 g6 $1 7. g4 h5 $1 $11 {Black is at
least fine here.}) 6... f5 7. c4 (7. Ne2 {I like this move more than the
immediate 7.c4} O-O 8. c4) 7... Be6 (7... f4 $5 {looks natural and strong for
Black too and this is one more reason why I prefer to start with 7.Nge2.}) (
7... dxc4 $5 {is another option} 8. Nxc4 Bb4+ 9. Kf1 {As you already know,
White's best setup is to put all his pawns on the dark squares, so the move
g2-g3 is part of White's plan anyway, and it is not a big deal that we lose
the right to castle.} O-O 10. Ne2 g6 11. h4 h5 12. Nf4 Nd7 13. Rh3 (13. Be2 {
[%cal Rd3e2,Re2f3] Transfering the bishop to the long diagonal is another plan
which you should remember. In general, the bishop is not very well placed on
"d3", especially against "f5-g6" setup.} Nf6 14. Bf3 Ne4 15. a3 Be7 16. g3 b6
17. Kg2 Bb7 18. Bxe4 fxe4 19. Ne5 $14) 13... Nf6 14. Qb3 a5 15. a3 Be7 16. Nb6
$14 {and I prefer White's position.}) 8. Ne2 (8. c5 Bc7 9. Ne2 Nd7 10. b4 {
We can keep the king for a bit longer in the center with an idea to avoid any
possible attack with h5-h4 with the rook still on "h8"} O-O 11. Qc2 g6 12. Rb1
Nf6 13. b5 Ne4 14. O-O $14 {Now we can safely castle and it is obvious that
Black's attack on the kingside is not dangerous. In the meantime, we already
put some pressure on the queenside.}) 8... Nd7 (8... dxc4 9. Bxc4 Qe7 10. Qb3
O-O 11. Bxe6 fxe6 12. Nc4 Bb4+ 13. Kf1 {[%csl Rb7,Re6][%cal Rg2g3,Rc4e5]} a5
14. a3 $14) 9. cxd5 $6 cxd5 {[%csl Rd5,Rf5]} 10. Nc3 O-O ({the solid} 10... Nf6
{is also possible}) 11. Qf3 g6 12. Nxd5 {Black sacrifices a pawn but get very
decent compensation for it.} Qa5 13. Nc3 Ba3 $1 14. Nb3 Qb4 15. Qe2 Rfc8 16.
Rc1 Bxb3 17. axb3 $2 (17. O-O $1 {was the best move here. White will take the
piece back with at least equal position.} Be6 18. bxa3 Qxa3 19. Qd2) 17... Qxb3
18. Rb1 Bxb2 19. Nd1 Bc3+ 20. Kf1 Qd5 $17 {Black is much better, probably
winning here, but it was a blitz game, and after many adventures, Mamedyarov
finally won the game.} 21. h4 h5 22. Rh3 Bxd4 23. exd4 Qxd4 24. Qe3 Qxe3 25.
Rxe3 Nc5 26. Nc3 a6 27. Be2 b5 28. Re7 Kf8 29. Nd5 Rd8 30. Bf3 Rab8 31. Ra7 Ra8
32. Rc7 Rac8 33. Ra7 Ra8 34. Rxa8 Rxa8 35. Rc1 Ne4 36. Bxe4 fxe4 37. Rc5 Rb8
38. Nc7 b4 39. Nxa6 Rb6 40. Rc8+ Kg7 41. Nxb4 Rxb4 42. g3 Kf6 43. Rc6+ Kf5 44.
Rc5+ Kf6 45. Rc6+ Kg7 46. Ke2 Rb3 47. Rc4 f5 48. Rc7+ Kf6 49. Rc6+ Kf7 50. Rc7+
Kf6 51. Rc6+ Kg7 52. Rc7+ Kh6 53. Ra7 Rb8 54. Rf7 Rg8 55. Ke3 Rg7 56. Rf6 Ra7
57. Rb6 Ra3+ 58. Ke2 Rc3 59. Ra6 Kg7 60. Ra7+ Kf6 61. Ra6+ Kf7 62. Ra7+ Kf6 63.
Ra6+ Kg7 64. Ra7+ Kh6 65. Rb7 Rc2+ 66. Ke3 Rc3+ 67. Ke2 Rc8 68. Ke3 Rg8 69. Kf4
Rg7 70. Rb6 Rd7 71. Ke3 Rd3+ 72. Ke2 Kg7 73. Rb7+ Kf6 74. Rb6+ Kf7 75. Rb7+ Ke6
76. Rg7 Kf6 77. Ra7 f4 78. Ra6+ Kf7 79. Ra7+ Ke6 80. Ra6+ Kf7 81. Ra7+ Kf6 82.
Ra6+ Kf7 83. Ra7+ Ke6 84. Ra6+ Kf5 85. Ra5+ Kf6 86. Ra6+ Kf5 87. Ra5+ Kg4 88.
Rg5+ Kh3 89. gxf4 Rf3 90. Rxg6 Rxf4 91. Ke3 Rf3+ 92. Kxe4 1-0

