{[%evp 0,93,40,35,27,4,11,-13,-13,-13,-6,-46,-38,-66,-38,-28,-21,-18,-14,-25,8,
-3,-4,-8,17,22,22,22,22,18,43,13,20,18,15,21,15,13,49,49,51,51,57,12,29,40,47,
57,72,60,60,36,40,35,37,29,46,37,34,25,62,44,50,47,36,34,42,18,49,29,42,38,70,
54,39,61,63,65,88,88,98,103,103,107,107,107,107,84,156,169,241,301,399,372,500,
414] This is a brilliant positional game by GM Kiril Georgiev} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5
d5 3. Bxf6 exf6 4. e3 c6 5. g3 {It is a very interesting plan. It is quite
solid and It was my choice over most of my career.} Bd6 6. Bg2 O-O ({The
reason why I stop using this plan for White is the following idea.} 6... f5 $1
{White keeps his king in the center and wants to attack on the kingside using
h7-h5} 7. Ne2 Nd7 8. O-O Nf6 9. Nd2 h5 $1 10. h4 {is a must for White} Ne4 11.
c4 g5 $1 $146 {Of course, the variation is not forced and even this position
is not so clear, but I hate to have my king attacked.}) 7. Ne2 {let me explain
to you few things about the plan with g3 and Bg2. First, it seems that the
bishop is not very active on g2, but it is not exactly the case. White wants
to put pressure on "d5," and the queenside and the bishop on g2 plays an
important role in this plan. Also, I should mention that the bishop is a great
defender. The other important point to remember is that we need to keep the
queenside knight on "b1" for a while. The point is that with the knight still
on b1, we are ready to met Qb6 with b3, followed by c4.} (7. Nd2 Qb6 8. b3 (8.
Rb1 Bf5 $1) 8... Ba3 {this move wouldn't be possible with the knight on b1})
7... Be6 8. O-O Nd7 9. Qd3 $1 {the idea is to support c4 and to stop Bf5.} f5
10. b3 Nf6 11. c4 {as you can see, GM Georgiev keeps his knight on b1, so he
can go immediately to c3 to put pressure on d5 and to support b4-b5.} Qd7 12.
Nbc3 Rac8 13. c5 $1 {I quite like this plan. White wins space on the queenside
when Black is totally without counterplay.} Bc7 14. b4 h5 15. h4 Rfe8 16. Nf4
Bxf4 {what else} 17. exf4 Ne4 18. Ne2 b5 {This move weakened the queenside,
but if Black didn't do this then White will simply proceed with the idea a4-b5,
Rfb1, etc...} 19. a4 a6 20. f3 Nf6 21. Ra3 {From now on the game is a perfect
example of good maneuvering and schematic thinking.} Qb7 22. Qd2 Ra8 23. Rfa1
Reb8 24. Bf1 Ne8 25. Nc1 Nc7 26. Nd3 f6 27. Be2 Qc8 28. Nc1 Bd7 29. Bd3 Qf8 30.
Ne2 Qe8 31. Kf2 g6 32. Nc3 Kg7 33. Nd1 Be6 34. Ne3 {White improves all his
pieces to maximum, and now it is time for the action.} Qd7 35. Qc2 Rh8 36. axb5
{First White relieves the tension on the queenside and then strikes on the
other side of the board} axb5 37. Ra7 Rxa7 38. Rxa7 Ra8 39. Rxa8 Nxa8 40. g4 $3
{the point of White's play} hxg4 41. fxg4 Qc7 42. Ng2 {[%cal Rh4h5,Rg2h4]} fxg4
43. Bxg6 Qa7 44. f5 Bf7 45. Qe2 Bxg6 46. Qxg4 Qa2+ 47. Kg3 {I quite like this
game. It is a real masterpiece which illustrates perfectly White's ideas in
such a position.} 1-0

