{[%evp 0,43,18,18,24,-1,4,-13,-9,-42,-23,-23,-23,-40,-23,1,13,22,45,41,48,75,
54,54,97,113,162,122,235,1,26,26,39,-114,38,168,29991,29992,29993,29994,29995,
29996,29999,29998,29999,-30000] In the last two games I will examine the
structure after 3...gxf6.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. Bxf6 gxf6 4. c4 {I prefer
this move order, mainly because I can met 4...c5 with 5.cxd5.} dxc4 (4... c5 5.
cxd5 $1 Qxd5 6. Nf3 cxd4 7. Nc3 Qa5 8. Nxd4 Bg7 9. e3 {I think it is easier to
play with White here.} ({or} 9. g3)) ({If Black chooses the setup with c6,
White is much better after} 4... c6 5. Nc3 e6 (5... e5 6. e3 {[%csl Rc6,Rd5,
Re5,Rf6] this is a really bad structure for Black} Be6 7. cxd5 cxd5 8. Bb5+ Nc6
9. Nge2 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Bxc6 $5 bxc6 12. Na4 $14 {[%csl Rc6,Re6,Re7][%cal
Ra1c1]}) 6. e3 f5 7. Nf3 {[%csl Rc8]} Bg7 {This structure with double f-pawns
can be always met with the idea h3-g4} 8. h3 $1 O-O (8... Nd7 9. g4 fxg4 10.
hxg4 Nf6 11. g5 Nd7 12. Qc2 $16) 9. g4 $36) 5. e3 c5 6. Bxc4 cxd4 (6... Nc6 {
can be met with} 7. Qb3 e6 8. d5 Na5 9. Qa4+ Bd7 10. Bb5 b6 11. Nc3 a6 12.
Bxd7+ Qxd7 13. Qf4 Be7 14. Rd1 $36) 7. Nc3 e6 (7... dxc3 $4 8. Bxf7+) (7... Nc6
{is well met by} 8. Qh5 e6 9. Rd1 $14) 8. exd4 Nc6 (8... f5 {is too slow here
and White should try to open the position with d5.} 9. Nf3 Bg7 10. O-O O-O 11.
Re1 a6 12. d5 $14) 9. Nf3 Be7 10. O-O {The main problem for Black is that his
king is not feeling well in the centre, where White can easily attack it with
Re1 and d5. The real problem is that the king si not safe on the kingside as
well.} O-O 11. Qd2 $1 $16 {[%cal Rd2h6]} b6 12. Rad1 Bb7 13. Qh6 Nb4 14. Qh5 (
14. d5 $1 Nxd5 15. Nxd5 Bxd5 16. Rxd5 exd5 17. Bd3 {with mate}) 14... Rc8 15.
Bb3 Nd5 16. Rd3 Kh8 17. Bxd5 Bxd5 18. Ng5 fxg5 19. Rh3 Be4 20. Nxe4 Kg7 21.
Qh6+ Kg8 22. Qxh7# 1-0

