0,0] In this game, I will show you how White should play, when Black is
playing without e6.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. Bg5 d5 3. e3 c5 4. Bxf6 gxf6 5. c4 dxc4 6.
Bxc4 cxd4 7. exd4 Bg7 8. Nc3 Nc6 9. Nge2 O-O 10. O-O Bg4 (10... f5 $5 {is more
popular, but always when Black plays this move, his light-squared bishop
becomes passive.}) 11. d5 {Black delays the move e6, and White immediately
takes advantage of this. Now White's position is preferable because there are
many weak squares in Black's camp as "f5" and "h5". In many lines, Black's
king will be in trouble. Nepomniachtchi saves the game but struggles a lot.}
Ne5 12. Bb3 Rc8 13. h3 Bd7 14. Ng3 $14 {Thanks to his space advantage and
better structure, White is better here.} Qb6 15. Qh5 Qd4 16. Bc2 Ng6 17. Bf5 (
17. Nf5 $1 Bxf5 18. Bxf5 $16 {[%cal Ra1d1]}) 17... Rfd8 18. Bxd7 Rxd7 19. Nf5
Qd2 20. Qg4 Rcd8 21. h4 Qf4 22. Qh3 e6 23. dxe6 fxe6 24. Nxg7 Kxg7 25. Qxe6
Qxh4 26. Rad1 Rxd1 27. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 28. Nxd1 Qd4 29. Ne3 Qxb2 30. Nf5+ Kf8 31. g3
